# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: university-of-oxford
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] The **2010 United Kingdom student protests** were a series of demonstrations in November and December 2010 that took place in several areas of the country, with the focal point of protests being in central London.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Largely student-led, the protests were held in opposition to planned spending cuts to further education and an increase of the cap on tuition fees by the Conservative–Liberal Democrat coalition government following their review into higher education funding in England.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Student groups said that the intended cuts to education were excessive, would damage higher education, give students higher debts, and broke campaign promises made by politicians.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] The first major demonstration occurred on 10 November, jointly organised by the National Union of Students (NUS) and the University and College Union (UCU).
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] It involved between 30,000 and 50,000 demonstrators marching through central London, with several hundred branching off to attack and occupy the Conservative Party headquarters.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] This measure brought condemnation from the establishment and a divide within the student movement over the appropriateness of such tactics.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] The National Campaign Against Fees and Cuts (NCAFC) called for a mass walk-out and demonstration on 24 November, with occupations taking place at campuses throughout the UK.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] A march in central London was kettled in Whitehall, resulting in violent confrontation with protesters.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Further demonstrations were held in central London on 30 November, when police clashed with protesters and kettled them in Trafalgar Square, while other protests took place throughout the country.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Another central London protest took place on 9 December, the day that the proposed reforms were passed into law, with protesters clashing with police and being kettled in Parliament Square.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] The student protests were unsuccessful in their aim of preventing the government's reforms in England.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] However, in Wales and Northern Ireland, devolved authorities decided not to increase the fees, which led to differing fee levels for the devolved nations.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] The demonstrations were highly controversial in the UK, being condemned for instances of violence and vandalism by both the establishment and by protestors.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] The behaviour of the Metropolitan Police in dealing with the protests was also widely criticised for alleged instances of untruthfulness and excessive use of force.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] In November 2009, the Labour Party government of Prime Minister Gordon Brown commissioned a study into higher education funding in England.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Chaired by Lord Browne of Madingley, the former chief executive of BP, the report was to be titled the Browne Review.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] In the build up to the 2010 general election, the leader of the Liberal Democrats, Nick Clegg, pledged that he would vote against any proposed increase in tuition fees if elected to Parliament.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Following the election and resulting hung parliament, Clegg made an agreement with the Conservative Party to form a coalition government in which Conservative leader David Cameron became Prime Minister and Clegg became Deputy Prime Minister.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] The Browne Review was subsequently published in October 2010, and contained the suggestion that the government should remove outright the existing cap of £3,290 on tuition fees.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] The government rejected this proposal, instead choosing to keep a cap but increasing it to £9,000.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] David Willetts, the Minister of State for Universities and Science, stated that the measures were "a very progressive package" and "at the end of this we will have a better university system than we have at the moment".
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Contravening his pre-election pledge, Clegg expressed support for the rise in the cap on tuition fees, which would result in future students paying higher fees for their university education.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Student union leaders were critical of the cuts.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] The National Union of Students (NUS) feared that the increased cap on tuition fees would prevent potential students from poorer backgrounds from attending university.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Many protesters focused in particular on Clegg's campaign promise that he would oppose any rise in tuition fees.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Two weeks before, on 28 October, a protest was held in the University of Oxford to coincide with a visit from the Liberal Democrat minister and Business Secretary Vince Cable.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Cable cancelled his visit after taking advice from the police about the protest.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Several days later, on 3 November, there was a student protest in Dublin.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] The subsequent London protest was described by one Irish reporter as "scenes bizarrely similar" to those in the Irish capital.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] The initial event was the largest student protest in Britain since the Labour government first proposed the Teaching and Higher Education Act in 1998.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] The first major demonstration in protest at the government's proposed reforms was held on 10 November 2010 in central London, jointly organised by the National Union of Students (NUS) and the University and College Union (UCU).
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] This demonstration was officially known as "Fund Our Future: Stop Education Cuts", although also termed "Demo 2010" or "Demo-lition 10.11.10".
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Arriving from all regions of Great Britain and Northern Ireland, approximately 30,000 to 52,000 protesters attended the demonstration.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Political groups that sent contingents to take part included the Labour Party, Plaid Cymru, the Green Party, Socialist Workers Party, Socialist Party, Revolution, Young Communist League, Revolutionary Communist Group, and Communist Students.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] A few members of parliament (MPs) joined the demonstration, among them Labour MP John McDonnell, who told reporters: "This is the biggest workers' and students' demonstration in decades.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] It just shows what can be done when people get angry.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Representatives of the National Pensioners Convention also took part, with the group's banner carrier, Janet Shapiro, stating that: "We're here because we believe education should be free, funded by the taxpayer.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Hunt stated that making the public university system in Britain "the most expensive in the world" was unfair, that discouraging young people from going to college was not progressive, and that the increase in tuition fees represented further debts for students.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] The rally was also addressed by NUS President Aaron Porter and the Trades Union Congress Deputy general secretary Frances O'Grady.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] O'Grady offered the message to the government that: "Don't you dare tell us we're all in this together.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] The deficit certainly wasn't caused by the students." The protest was scheduled to end at 2 pm, but slightly overran.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] The Metropolitan Police were expecting 20,000 demonstrators to turn out, well below the 50,000 figure most widely quoted in the press after the event, and did not expect any violence, so deployed only 225 officers to police the event.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] In the afternoon, as protesters passed the Houses of Parliament and moved towards Tate Britain for the rally, several thousand surrounded 30 Millbank in Westminster, campaign headquarters of the Conservative Party, despite attempts by NUS organisers to stop them.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Forcing their way past the limited police presence, approximately 200 people broke in and occupied the building, whilst a thousand more cheered and supported them from outside.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] These protesters lit placards on fire, and smashed windows before occupying and vandalising the reception area.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Staff working in the building were evacuated by police around 1 pm.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Around 100 protesters proceeded to the roof of the building, chanting slogans including "Greece!
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Initial press sources blamed this action on a group of anarchists.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] This was later disputed, with a reporter from *The Guardian* noting that most of the protesters occupying the building were students who had been radicalised in opposition to the cuts, and were not all political anarchists.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Riot police from the Territorial Support Group arrived an hour after the building was occupied to remove the protesters.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] In retaliation, the police were pelted with eggs, rotten fruit, banners, and shards of glass.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] One of the protesters on the building's roof, Edward Woolard, threw a fire extinguisher onto the police below.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] He received instant criticism from some of the protesting crowds, who called on those on the roof to "stop throwing shit".
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] To control the situation, police used the controversial technique of kettling to trap the protesters within Millbank Square, the forecourt to 30 Millbank, whilst protesters on the outside of the building were pushed back.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] The police began letting demonstrators out of the building from 6:30 pm, arresting those whom they believed were responsible for vandalism.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] In all, 14 people were injured and required hospitalisation, at least three of whom were police officers, whilst police arrested 35 of the demonstrators, sending them off to various police stations around the city.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Later accounts that the numbers arrested had risen to 54, (33 men and 21 women), ten of whom were aged under 18 and the majority of whom were students.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] The actions of a minority, out of 50,000 people, is regrettable." Oxford University's Student Union (OUSU) President David Barclay issued a statement declaring that "OUSU supports the rights of students to protest non-violently.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Contrastingly, other student leaders, trade unionists, and academics expressed support for elements of the occupation of 30 Millbank.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Meanwhile, various university Conservative societies around London condemned the protests, and criticised students' unions for providing the "false impression that the majority of students are left-wing" and opposed to the governments' proposed reforms.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] The Metropolitan Police Service admitted that they were unprepared to deal with the occupation of 30 Millbank, something which they had not been expecting.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Sir Paul Stephenson, the Metropolitan Police's Commissioner, told the press that he was "embarrassed" by how police had lost control of the situation, and condemned what he saw as "thuggish, loutish behaviour by criminals".
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Stephenson remarked that "the one thing I would say is that it must have been an awful time for the people trying to go about their daily business in those buildings.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] I feel terribly sorry that they have had to go through what must have been quite a traumatic experience...
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] We are determined to make sure that sort of thing does not happen again on our streets.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] I'm clear on that, the Met is clear on that." His views were echoed by Mayor of London Boris Johnson, who stated: "This is intolerable and all those involved will be pursued and they will face the full force of the law...
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] The Metropolitan Police commissioner has assured me that there will be a vigorous post-incident investigation.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Prime Minister David Cameron condemned the occupation of Millbank, stating that he would not abandon his position on the issue of education cuts.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Speaking from the 2010 G20 Seoul summit in South Korea, Cameron said the occasion had been "extremely serious" and praised the "bravery" of the police officers.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] He also stated that the actions of the protesters were "unacceptable" and that "I was worried for the safety of the people in the building because I know people who work there".
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] The following morning, Clegg went on ITV's *Daybreak* to state: "I should have been more careful perhaps in signing that pledge [to not increase tuition fees]...
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] At the time [prior to his election] I really thought we could do it.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] The *Financial Times* reported that an anonymous vice-chancellor from a London university had told them that the violence would undermine the campaign, and that it "could not have gone better for the government.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] In the following days, smaller protests were held in Manchester and Cambridge, with no violent confrontations.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] On 11 November, student protesters occupied a building at the University of Manchester for three hours, demanding to see the accounts that discussed how government funding cuts would affect students.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Between 60 and 100 students held a peaceful sit-in at Manchester's John Owens Building on Oxford Road after an NUS meeting earlier that day.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Representing this group, protester Jeremy Buck said: "This is just what a few students who had the energy left after the London demo managed to achieve...
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Imagine what will happen when they have enough time to organise properly for the 24th.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] It is a matter of watch this space." That same day, protesters at the University of Cambridge held a demonstration against the cuts at the university's annual science, engineering and technology careers fair.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] On 23 November, anti-education cuts protesters had assembled outside of the offices of *The Guardian* newspaper, where Clegg was giving his Hugo Young lecture.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] They brought out an effigy of Clegg, sentencing it to death and executing it by hanging, shouting the slogan "Nick Clegg, shame on you, shame on you for turning blue".
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] A second significant demonstration took place in London on 24 November, which again led to clashes with police, this time outside Whitehall, after police kettled a large crowd.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] An organisation known as the National Campaign Against Fees and Cuts (NCAFC) organised a mass national walk-out of education and protest for 24 November.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] As a part of this, demonstrations were held in London and other locations across the United Kingdom.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] The NCAFC encouraged protesters to use social media to invite others to join them.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Several thousand protesters, most of whom were students or school children, gathered in Trafalgar Square, central London, late in the morning.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] They proceeded toward Whitehall shouting the slogan, "fuck David Cameron".
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Believing that there had been a lack of officers at 10 November demonstration, the Metropolitan Police drafted in 1000 police officers from across Greater London to oversee the event, almost five times the number at 10 November.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Police informed press that they planned to monitor fringe elements within the demonstration whom they believed planned to encourage "vandalism and violence".
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] At Whitehall, just before 1 pm, police prevented the protesters from reaching Parliament Square and the Houses of Parliament, setting up a line of riot police to kettle the protesters.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] A reporter *The Guardian* described the crowd at this point as being "predominantly good natured, although very noisy".
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Nonetheless, the demonstrators tried to push through the police line, leading to clashes.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] An unoccupied police van which had been left in the midst of the crowd was vandalised; protesters rocked it back and forth, climbed on its roof, smashed its windows, wrote graffiti on it and threw a smoke bomb inside.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] A group of school girls encircled the van, urging people not to vandalise it.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] At around 6 pm, mounted police charged at the north end of the crowd to push them back; despite video evidence police denied that this was an actual charge, describing it as crowd control using horses.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Various bus shelters and ticket machines in the area were vandalised, with Transport for London diverting buses away from the unrest.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Approximately 200 protesters were unable to escape and remained kettled in Whitehall.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Police falsely informed press that the crowd were provided with toilet facilities and water; protesters disputed these claims on social media, with ULU President Clare Solomon commenting on Facebook: "we're still illegally kettled in the freezing cold on Whitehall.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] No food, water or toilets despite what the police are telling the media.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Thousands of young people needing to go home." To keep warm, protesters set fire to a ticket machine within the Square, prompting riot police to secure the machine and put out the flames.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] From 9 to 10 pm, police permitted the rest of the Whitehall protesters to leave, approximately nine to ten hours after they had first been contained, some being searched as they left.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] During the clashes, police arrested 41 protesters.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Across the UK, protesters occupied university buildings in at least 12 universities.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] On 23 November, protesters occupied the picture gallery corridor of Royal Holloway, University of London.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] They were later joined by supportive members of university staff who took part in what was labelled a "teach-in".
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] On 24 November, the Language Centre at London South Bank University was occupied for 51 hours by over 100 students as part of the "Defend LSBU!
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] They're quoting Harry Potter rather than Che Guevara." Protesters also occupied the University of East London, demanding that university managers "put pressure on the government on the issue of H[higher] E[ducation] cuts and tuition fee rises".
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] A group of about 100 occupied a lecture theatre in the Roscoe Building.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] At the University of Oxford, students initially occupied the Radcliffe Camera.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] At the University of Cambridge, 200 students scaled the fence of Senate House and marched onto the grounds of King's College, then on 26 November students started an 11-day occupation of part of Old Schools, the main administrative block of the university.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] At the University of Bristol, 2000 protesters clashed with police when they tried to move into the city centre.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] In Brighton, 3000 demonstrators marched through the city, with nearly 50 occupying a university building.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Hundreds of students from Kingston University and various local schools staged an impromptu march through the town and a sit down protest at College Roundabout, leading to one arrest.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Hundreds of them had walked out of the local Allerton Grange High School to join the demonstration, and later occupied the Michael Sadler lecture theatre and a room at Leeds Metropolitan University.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] A room at the University of Plymouth was also occupied.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] At Cardiff University, around 200 protesters occupied a lecture theatre after failing to gain entry to the vice-chancellor's building.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] During the Whitehall incident, the Metropolitan Police publicly defended their use of kettling, with Chief Inspector Jane Connors claiming that they had only used it as "a last resort".
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] At a meeting of the Metropolitan Police Authority the following day, the Metropolitan Police's Commissioner Sir Paul Stephenson defended the tactics.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] He was criticised by Jenny Jones, a Green Party member of the London Assembly, who told him: "when you imprison thousands of people, which is essentially what you did yesterday, you do have a duty of care to them...
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] You kept people for nine-and-a-half hours.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] A spokesperson for Prime Minister Cameron stated that "people have a right to engage in lawful and peaceful protest, but there is no place for violence or intimidation", while education minister David Willetts responded by claiming that protesting students did not understand the government's plans.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Clegg stated on BBC Radio 2 that "I hate in politics, as in life, to make promises that you then find you can't keep.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] We made a promise we can't deliver – we didn't win the election outright and there are compromises in coalition." Labour Party leader Ed Miliband stated that he would not rule out joining further demonstrations, remarking that "I was quite tempted to go out and talk to them [the protesters].
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Peaceful demonstrations are part of our society.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] A third central London protest was organised for Tuesday 30 November, a day that saw cold temperatures and snow in the city.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Protesters assembled at Trafalgar Square, but a police line prevented their march down Whitehall towards the Houses of Parliament; the NCAFC accused the Police of "pre-emptively block[ing]" the protest route.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Fearing that they would be kettled in the Square, protesters dispersed throughout the city center, pursued by police.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Other officers stood photographing and filming the students for later identification, while police vans blocked off certain streets.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Some protesters chanted "Peaceful protest!
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Peaceful protest!" and "no ifs, no buts, no education cuts", and others blew vuvuzelas and played reggae from portable stereo systems.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] A BBC reporter talked to members of the demonstration, noting that while many desired a peaceful outcome, others believed that violent confrontation with the police was inevitable.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Many were angry with how they had been portrayed in the media, with one commenting that confrontation was not caused by "hardcore anarchists" but by "students who are very, very angry".
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Many protesters ran onto Pall Mall and then past St James's Park.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Denied access to Parliament Square by police, they turned around and headed toward Westminster Abbey.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] A reporter from *The Guardian* noted that "the march is fracturing – people are going up different streets and getting lost.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] The police kettled those in the Square, whilst some of the protesters waved banners with slogans such as "Don't put the kettle on, Mr.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Cameron" and "I Can't Believe It's Not Thatcher".
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] The police "put lines [of officers] across all the exits" to the kettled area of the Square, but reportedly allowed small groups of protesters to leave, even though the majority, around 150 to 200, decided to stay and continue protesting in the snow.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Some protesters burned placards and one spray-painted the word "Revolution" on Nelson's Column.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Others threw plastic bottles and fireworks at police lines, and at one point there "was a scuffle as a knot of policemen rushed one of the protesters, grabbing him to arrest him, and the crowd flocked angrily to the area".
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] At another time, a group of riot police moved into the crowd of protesters to attempt to secure Nelson's Column, only to be surrounded by demonstrators shouting "Who's kettling who?
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] We're kettling you!" Other slogans shouted at police during the protest included "Shame on you!" and "Your job's next".
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Police then arrested 146 demonstrators who refused to leave the Square; 139 of them were arrested for breach of the peace, whilst seven were arrested on suspicion of violent disorder.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Seven more had been arrested in central London earlier in the day.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] The night before, on 28 November, a crowd of two to three hundred protesters gathered outside of Lewisham Town Hall in Catford, south London, where a council meeting was then in progress, to protest against wider public sector cuts.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Several Youtube videos of the incident were shown on national news, including the BBC.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Many of the protesters had come from nearby sixth forms (due to potential Education Maintenance Allowance cuts) and also from Goldsmiths College.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Demonstrators, playing music and political slogans from boomboxes forced their way into the building, where a smoke bomb was let off, while another protester climbed onto the roof and unfurled a banner.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Several more flares were set off outside and windows smashed, with riot police from the Territorial Support Group close by, were called and several arrests were made.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] One of the protesters, Sue Luxton, a former Green Party councillor who had subsequently become a teacher, told the press that "I wanted to peacefully express my anger at the cuts...
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] On the day of the main demonstration, there were also further protests across the United Kingdom, including in Cardiff, Cambridge, Colchester, Newcastle, Bath, Leeds, Sheffield, Edinburgh, Liverpool, Belfast, Brighton, York, Manchester, Plymouth, Scunthorpe and Bristol.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] About 1,500 students, including school children, took part in the protest in Brighton, whilst protests in Bristol involved police being pelted with mustard and ten demonstrators were arrested.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] In Sheffield, police were pelted with snowballs as they guarded the constituency office of Nick Clegg from a crowd of two hundred protesters.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] The British protests coincided with those in Italy, where demonstrations occurred in Milan, Turin, Naples, Venice, Palermo, Bari, Genoa, and Rome where riot police were called in to prevent students from gaining access to the parliament building.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Meanwhile, whilst occupations that had begun the previous week continued at University College London, Newcastle University and the University of Cambridge, a new one began at the University of Nottingham, where 150 protesters occupied a building.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] University buildings and local government buildings were occupied in Birmingham and Oxford while police blocked an attempt at occupation of the council building in York.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] The protesters occupying the council chamber in Birmingham left after four hours, with a police spokesperson commending the protesters for their "wholly peaceful" behaviour, and noting that it "couldn't have been more different from the violent clashes seen recently in London".
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] ULU members handed out green hard hats with the words "Tax the banks, not the students" on them, whilst a rally was held in Bloomsbury at midday, where ULU President Solomon addressed the crowd.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] The Metropolitan Police had positioned lines of riot police and police vans along the Houses of Parliament, to prevent any protesters gaining access to it.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Superintendent Julia Pendry issued a statement saying: "Protesters will be allowed sight and sound of parliament.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] However, there is evidence to suggest a number of people will come to London intent on causing violence and disorder.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] The protesters marched from Bloomsbury to Parliament Square in the afternoon, where they pushed down metal barriers and occupied the Square.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Around 3:30 pm, police kettled those several thousand protesters in the square, preventing them from leaving, stating that it was necessary "due to the level of violence that our officers are facing".
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Mounted police charged into the crowd on one side of the Square in an attempt to disperse them.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] A field hospital was set up on the green providing emergency first aid to protesters as well as tea and food within the containment area.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Around 30 protesters were treated, most for head injuries.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Police used batons to hit protesters, and a St John Ambulance member told press that he had treated ten protesters for head injuries from being struck by police batons by 4.30 pm.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] One protester, philosophy student Alfie Meadows, suffered a blow to the head from a police truncheon that knocked him unconscious.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Taken to hospital, it was discovered that he was suffering from bleeding of the brain, and required brain surgery.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Reporter Jonathan Haynes of *The Guardian*, who was present, characterised the police tactics as "very heavy handed".
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Police informed press that they were allowing young and vulnerable protesters to leave the kettle, but those inside the kettle, including journalists, asserted that this was untrue.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] At 5:41 pm, news reached the protesters that the government had voted to support the proposals.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Clashes ensued between the crowd and the police, and the protesters pulled along metal fencing to separate themselves from riot police, who were trying to push them all into the centre of the Square.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Later on in the evening, with the protesters still kettled in the Square, protesters smashed all of the windows on the ground floor of Her Majesty's Treasury.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] At 21:15, the protest was forced onto Westminster Bridge where it was kettled until approximately 23:30.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Due to the Parliament Square protest being kettled, many other demonstrators could not enter the Square and so disseminated across much of the rest of central London.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Meanwhile, many of those students who remained around the area of Trafalgar Square continued to protest, with about 150 holding a sit-in in the adjacent National Gallery, while others attempted to set fire to the Trafalgar Square Christmas tree.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] During the protests, a car taking The Prince of Wales and The Duchess of Cornwall to the evening's Royal Variety Performance at the London Palladium was attacked on Regent Street and Home Secretary Theresa May confirmed a protester 'made contact' with Camilla.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] In Oxford Street, Topshop was damaged, as rioters sprayed "pay your tax" on the building and broke windows.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Home Secretary Theresa May issued a statement in which she "utterly condemned" the actions of the protesters, and declared that "What we are seeing in London tonight, the wanton vandalism, smashing of windows, has nothing to do with peaceful protest...
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Nearly 50 people complained to the Independent Police Complaints Commission (IPCC) about police behaviour during the various protests held around the country, with the majority directed against the Metropolitan Police, including complaints of violence used against protesters.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Following the protests, video footage posted on YouTube showed Jody McIntyre, a protester with cerebral palsy, involved in an altercation with police.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] The footage showed McIntyre, who had positioned himself in the front line facing police, being pulled out of his wheelchair and dragged across the ground by Metropolitan Police officers.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] While McIntyre later said he had been pulled out of the wheelchair twice, only one incident is shown in the video.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] On 13 December, he was interviewed about the incident by BBC journalist Ben Brown, an interview later described by *The Guardian* newspaper as "having a distinct lack of sympathy from the BBC" and it was noted that the incident had "attracted thousands of complaints".
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] McIntyre's complaint was later rejected by Scotland Yard.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] His subsequent appeal was partly upheld by the IPCC.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Street medics treated student protesters during the parliament square protest on Thursday 9 December, the day of the scheduled vote to raise university tuition fees.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] A field tent was set up on the green providing emergency first aid to protesters as well as tea and food within the containment area.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Alfie Meadows was acquitted of all charges in 2013.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] In September 2023 the Metropolitan Police apologised to him and agreed a financial settlement.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] On 30 November, following the third main day of protesting, the Welsh Assembly announced that it would not permit an increase in fees for Welsh students.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] In July 2011, three school children will challenge the kettling of children at the 24 November 2010 protest.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] In September 2011, students in Northern Ireland succeeded in getting the Northern Ireland Assembly to freeze tuition fees, avoiding the large fee increases in England.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Student leaders in Northern Ireland cited the wider protests across the UK as one reason for their success.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] As of 2020, this has saved Northern Ireland university students £1 billion in tuition fees compared to English students.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] In November 2012, two years after the 2010 demonstrations, protests ignited again from the student movement.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Organised by the NUS, around 10,000 demonstrators marched in central London.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Cooper complained that the allegations were untrue, threatened his future academic prospects and left his reputation "as badly trashed" as the Millbank Tower.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] The years following the student protests saw a leftward shift in the politics of the NUS.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] In 2014 the NUS Conference voted in support of free education, reversing the union's previous policy of advocating a graduate tax as a replacement for tuition fees, which it had adopted in the late 2000s.
[src:university-of-oxford/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] The Student Broad Left made progressive gains in the mid-2010s, culminating in the election of SBL candidate Malia Bouattia as NUS President.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] The **A-level** (**Advanced Level**) is a main school leaving qualification of the General Certificate of Education in England, Wales, Northern Ireland, the Channel Islands and the Isle of Man.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] It is available as an alternative qualification in other countries, where it is similarly known as an A-Level.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] Students generally study for A-levels over a two-year period.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] For much of their history, A-levels have been examined by written exams taken at the end of these two years.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] In 2015, Ofqual decided to change back to a terminal approach where students sit all examinations at the end of the second year.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] AS is still offered, but as a separate qualification; AS grades no longer count towards a subsequent A-level in England.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] Most students study three or four A-level subjects simultaneously during the two post-16 years (ages 16–18) in a secondary school, in a sixth form college, in a further and higher education college, or in a tertiary college, as part of their further education.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] In the UK, some schools and colleges offer one-year A Level retake programmes for students who wish to improve their grades.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] A-levels were introduced in 1951 as a standardised school-leaving qualification, replacing the Higher School Certificate.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] The examinations were taken on a subject-by-subject basis, the subjects being chosen according to the strengths and interests of the student.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] This encouraged specialization and in-depth study of three to four subjects.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] At first, A-levels were graded as simply distinction, pass or fail (although students were given an indication of their marks, to the nearest 5%).
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] Candidates obtaining a distinction originally had the option to sit a scholarship level paper on the same material, to attempt to win one of 400 national scholarships.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] The scholarship level was renamed the S-Level in 1963.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] Quite soon, rising numbers of students taking the A-level examinations required more differentiation of achievement below the S-Level standard.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] Grades were therefore introduced, with recommendations by the Secondary School Examinations Council (SSEC) of approximate proportions of pupils for each grade.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] The O grade was equivalent to a GCE Ordinary Level pass which indicated a performance equivalent to the lowest pass grade at Ordinary Level.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] Over time, the validity of this system was questioned because, rather than reflecting a standard, norm referencing simply maintained a specific proportion of candidates at each grade, which in small cohorts was subject to statistical fluctuations in standards.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] In 1984, the government's Secondary Examinations Council decided to replace the norm referencing with criterion referencing: grades would in future be awarded on examiner judgement thus eliminating a possible inadequacy of the existing scheme.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] The criterion referencing scheme came into effect for the summer 1987 exams as the system set examiners specific criteria for the awarding of B and E grades to candidates, and then divided out the other grades according to fixed percentages.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] Rather than awarding an Ordinary Level for the lowest pass, a new "N" (for Nearly passed) was introduced.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] Criticisms of A-level grading continued, and when Curriculum 2000 was introduced, the decision was made to have specific criteria for each grade, and the 'N' grade was abolished.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] In 1989, Advanced Supplementary (AS) awards were introduced; they were intended to broaden the subjects a pupil studied post 16, and were to complement rather than be part of a pupil's A-level studies.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] AS-Levels were generally taken over two years, and in a subject the pupil was not studying at A-Level.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] Each AS level contained half the content of an A-Level, and at the same level of difficulty.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] Initially, a student might study three subjects at A-Level and one at AS-Level, or often even four subjects at A-Level.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] However, due to decreasing public spending on education over time, a growing number of schools and sixth form colleges would now arrange for their pupils to study for three A-Levels instead of four.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] A-levels evolved gradually from a two-year linear course with an exam at the end, to a modular course, between the late 1980s and 2000.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] By the year 2000 there was a strong educational reason to standardise the exam and offer greater breadth to students through modules and there was also a pragmatic case based on the inefficiency of linear courses where up to 30% of students were failing to complete or pass.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] Curriculum 2000 was introduced in September 2000, with the first new examinations taken in January and June of the following year.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] The Curriculum 2000 reforms also replaced the S-Level extension paper with the Advanced Extension Award.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] The Conservative Party under Prime Minister David Cameron initiated reforms for A-levels to change from modular to the current linear structure.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] British Examination Boards (Edexcel, AQA and OCR) regulated and accredited by the government of the United Kingdom responded to the government's reform announcements by modifying specifications of several A-level subjects.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] On 18 March 2020, A-level examinations were cancelled in order to curtail the spread of COVID-19 in the 2019–2020 coronavirus pandemic.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] The A-level and AS-level qualifications would instead be awarded based upon a mix of teacher assessment and informal "mock" exams taken earlier in the school year.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] On 6 January 2021, Secretary of State for Education Gavin Williamson confirmed that the 2020/21 series of A-levels would also be cancelled, pending further arrangements by Ofqual and the Department for Education.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] Prior to the 2015 government reforms of the A-level system, A-levels had (since the Curriculum 2000 reforms) consisted of two equally weighted parts: AS (Advanced Subsidiary) Level, usually assessed in the first year of study, and "A2 Level", usually assessed in the second year of study.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] It was typical for an AS course to comprise two or three modules, with the A2 half of the course comprising two or three modules, for a total of four or six modules.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] The modules within each part may have been equally weighted, or be of varying weights.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] Modules were either assessed by externally marked papers, or by school-assessed, externally moderated coursework.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] Following the reforms, A-Levels and AS-Levels have been decoupled, with AS-Level results no longer counting towards the A-Level qualification.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] The AS-Level consists of the first half of the A-Level course, and can be taught alongside the first year of the full A-Level course.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] Grades are determined by adding up the mark for each component (which is sometimes weighted) and applying a grade boundary.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] A wide variety of subjects are offered at A-level by the five exam boards.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] Although exam boards often alter their curricula, this table shows the majority of subjects which are consistently available for study.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] The number of A-level exams taken by students can vary.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] A typical route is to study four subjects at AS level and then drop down to three at A2 level, although some students continue with their fourth subject.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] Three is usually the minimum number of A-levels required for university entrance, with some universities specifying the need for a fourth AS subject.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] There is no limit set on the number of A-levels one can study, and a number of students take five or more A-levels.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] It is permissible to take A-levels in languages one already speaks fluently, or courses with overlapping content, even if not always fully recognized by universities.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] There are many options that are in place for students to choose to do coursework.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] Those who do not reach the minimum standard required for a grade E receive the non-grade **U** (ungraded/unclassified), and those who fail to complete any of the subject's components will receive an **X**.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] The process to decide these grades for modular A-levels involves the uniform mark scheme (UMS).
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] Under this scheme, four-module A-levels have a maximum mark of 400 UMS (or 200 UMS each for AS and A2), and six-module A-levels have a maximum mark of 600 (or 300 UMS each for AS and A2).
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] The maximum UMS within AS and A2 may be split unequally between each modules.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] For example, a Physics AS may have two exam modules worth 90 UMS and 150 UMS, and a coursework module worth 60 UMS.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] The 'raw marks' i.e. actual score received on a test may differ from UMS awarded.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] On each assignment, the correspondence of raw marks to UMS is decided by setting grade boundaries, a process which involves consultation by subject experts and consideration of statistics, aiming to keep standards for each grade the same year on year.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] Achieving less than 40% results in a U (unclassified).
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] For passing grades, 40% corresponds to an E grade, 50% a D, 60% a C, 70% a B, and 80% an A.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] The A* grade was introduced in 2010 and is awarded to candidates who average 80% UMS across all modules, with a score over 90% UMS in all A2 modules.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] In Mathematics, which comprises six 100 UMS modules, only the C3 and C4 modules count towards this requirement.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] In Further Mathematics and Additional Further Mathematics, where more than three A2 modules can be taken, the three best-scoring A2 modules count.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] Recent research and the corresponding findings have shown that over a time span of several years students from Northern Ireland outperformed students from England and Wales in A-level examinations.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] According to UCAS and HKEAA, the Hong Kong A-level examination has historically been benchmarked against the UK A-levels.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] In general, a UK A grade is broadly equivalent to a Hong Kong A-C grade.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] This conclusion is based mainly on the percentage of pupils achieving the respective grades in respective exams.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] In the UK, on average 25% of participants of each subject achieved an A grade every year, compared to the 25% A-C rate in Hong Kong – A(4%), A-B (10%), A-C (25%).
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] According to the BBC, the percentage of students achieving an A* is about 8–10%, which essentially lies within the A-B range of their Hong Kong counterparts in respective subjects.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] In the United States of America the high school diploma is the qualification generally required for entry into colleges and universities.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] Students are usually evaluated and granted admission to US higher education institutions based on a combination of school marks, via a transcript from their high school, and a college entrance exam, most commonly the SAT or ACT.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] In the United Kingdom, the high school diploma is considered to be at the level of the General Certificate of Secondary Education (GCSE), which is awarded at Year 11.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] For college and university admissions, the high school diploma may be accepted in lieu of the GCSE if an average grade of C is obtained in subjects with a GCSE counterpart.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] As the more academically rigorous A-levels awarded at Year 13 are expected for university admission, the high school diploma alone is generally not considered to meet university requirements.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] College Entrance Examination Board (CEEB) tests, such as the SAT, SAT Subject Tests, or the ACT, may also be considered.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] The Universities and Colleges Admissions Service (UCAS) recommends that in addition to a high school diploma, grades of 3 or above in at least two, or ideally three, Advanced Placement exams may be considered as meeting general entry requirements for admission.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] Access arrangements must be approved by the exam board concerned.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] There are others available, but these are the most commonly used.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] A-level examinations in the UK are currently administered through 5 examination boards: AQA, OCR, Edexcel (London Examinations), WJEC/Eduqas and CCEA.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] The present 5 can trace their roots via a series of mergers or acquisitions to one or more of the originally 9 GCE Examination boards.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] Additionally, there are four examination boards offering A-level qualifications internationally: OxfordAQA, Edexcel, Learning Resource Network (LRN) and the CIE.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] OCR and CIE are both branches of the parent organisation, Cambridge Assessment.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] OxfordAQA is a partnership between AQA and Oxford University Press.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] In the UK it is customary for schools to register with multiple examination boards and to "mix and match" A-levels to get a combined curriculum that fits the school profile.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] The exam boards finance themselves through the fees charged to the schools for administering the examination.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] In addition to the centre registration fee, A-level Mathematics will raise £120.00 per student, while Biology, Physics and Chemistry £90.00 per subject and languages such as Spanish, French and German £100.00 or £201.15 depending on the syllabus.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] A-levels are usually studied by students in Sixth Form, which refers to the last two years of secondary education in England, Wales and Northern Ireland, taken at ages 16–18.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] Some secondary schools have their own Sixth Form, which admits students from lower year groups, but will often accept external applications.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] There are also many specialist Sixth Form and Further Education Colleges which admit from feeder schools across a large geographic area.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] Admission to A-level programmes is at the discretion of providers, and usually depends on GCSE grades.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] A typical requirement would be 5 A*-C grades at GCSE, although requirements can be higher, particularly for independent schools and grammar schools.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] A-levels are offered as an alternate qualification by a small number of educational institutions in Scotland, in place of the standard Scottish Higher, and the Advanced Higher levels of the Scottish Qualifications Certificate.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] The schools that offer A-levels are mainly private fee-paying schools particularly for students wishing to attend university in England.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] Many international schools choose to use the British system for their wide recognition.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] Furthermore, students may choose to sit the papers of British examination bodies at education centres around the world, such as those belonging to the British Council.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] According to the British Council, A-levels are similar to the American Advanced Placement courses which are themselves equivalent to first-year courses of America's four-year bachelor's degrees.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] A-level students often apply to universities before they have taken their final exams, with applications administered centrally through UCAS.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] British universities (including Scottish universities, which receive many applicants taking A-levels) consider GCSEs, AS-level results, predicted A-level results, and extracurricular accomplishments when deciding whether applicants should be made an offer through UCAS.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] These offers may be 'unconditional', guaranteeing a place regardless of performance in A2 examinations.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] Far more often, the offers are conditional on A-level grades, and become void should the student fail to achieve the marks expected by the university (for example, conditional offer of three A-levels at grades B-B-C).
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] Universities may specify which subjects they wish these grades to be in (for example, conditional offer of grades A-A-B with a grade A in Mathematics).
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] The offer may include additional requirements, such as attaining a particular grade in the Sixth Term Examination Paper.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] The university is obliged to accept the candidate if the conditions are met, but is not obliged to reject a candidate who misses the requirements.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] Leniency may in particular be shown if the candidate narrowly misses grades.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] A-level grades are also sometimes converted into numerical scores, typically UCAS tariff scores.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] Under the new UCAS system starting in 2017, an A* grade at A-level is worth 56 points, while an A is worth 48, a B is worth 40, a C is worth 32, a D is 24, and a E is worth 16; so a university may instead demand that an applicant achieve 112 points, instead of the equivalent offer of B-B-C.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] This allows greater flexibility to students, as 112 points could also, for example, be achieved through the combination A-B-D, which would not have met the requirements of a B-B-C offer because of the D grade.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] Depending on the specific offer made, a combination of more than 3 subjects (typically 4 or 5) with lower grades, or points from non-academic input such as higher level music grades or a Key Skills course, may also be accepted by the university.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] The text of the offer determines whether this flexibility is available – "112 UCAS Points" likely would, while "112 UCAS Points from three A-level subjects" would not.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] There are currently three examination boards which provide an international variant of the United Kingdom A-level examinations to international students.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] These are Cambridge International Examinations (CIE), Edexcel and OxfordAQA.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] 2020-21 due to COVID-19 grades were teacher awarded, rather than examined.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] The most common criticism of the A-level system is an accusation of grade inflation.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] The press have noted the steady rise in average grades for several consecutive years and drawn the conclusion that A-levels are becoming consistently easier.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] A 2007 report by Robert Coe compared students' scores in the ALIS ability test with equivalent grades achieved in A-level exams over a period of approximately 20 years; he found that students of similar ability were achieving on average about 2 grades higher than in the past.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] In the case of maths it was nearer to 3.5 grades higher.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] The government and teaching bodies maintain that the improved grades represent higher levels of achievement due to improved and more experienced teaching methods, but some educationalists and journalists argue that the change is due to grade inflation and the examinations getting easier.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] It has also been suggested that government pressure on schools to achieve high examination results has led them to coach students to pass the examination rather than understand the subject.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] In 2000, the A-level system was changed to examine students at the end of each of the two years of A-level study, rather than only at the end of the two years.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] The results of the first year's exam (AS-level) allowed students to drop subjects they find difficult after one year and to retake AS examinations to achieve a higher grade at that level.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] The availability to resit the AS paper, with the best mark contributing to the full A level, has improved results of the A level.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] Some believe that students are tending to select easier subjects in order to achieve higher grades.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] Universities in Britain have complained that the increasing number of A grades awarded makes it hard to distinguish between students at the upper end of the ability spectrum.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] Many universities administer their own entrance tests such as the BMAT and LNAT for specific courses, or conduct interviews to select applicants.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] In 2005, the head of admissions at the University of Cambridge outlined changes he believed should be made to the current system, particularly the use of the Advanced Extension Awards, a more challenging qualification based on the more advanced content of the A-level syllabus.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] More universities have wanted to see applicants' individual module results to see how comfortably they have achieved their result due to fears that the A-level might not offer an accurate test of ability, or that it is a good prediction of future academic success.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] In 2002, allegations that students had been given lower marks than they deserved in order to fix overall results and make the pass rate seem lower than it had been in previous years were raised.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] The Tomlinson Inquiry was set up to ascertain whether this was an underhand way to disprove that A-levels were becoming too easy.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] As a result, some papers were re-marked but only 1,220 A-level and 733 AS-level students saw an improvement to their results.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] To replace the cancelled summer 2020 examination series (owing to concerns over the spread of COVID-19), grades were awarded using *centre-assessed grades* and rankings.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] These were initially moderated by Ofqual but, owing to numerous problems, candidates' final grades reverted to those supplied by centres.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] This resulted in significant grade inflation, with initial calculations showing around 37.7% of candidates gaining a grade A or A*, compared with 25.2% in 2019.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] In response to concerns shown by employers and universities that it was not possible to distinguish exceptional candidates among the large number of students achieving A grades, and in order to mirror GCSE standards, a higher "super A" grade (like the A* grade at GCSE) was proposed in 2004.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] For modular A2 exams sat from 2010 onwards, the highest A-level grade is A*, requiring an A grade overall and 90% overall average UMS in A2 papers.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] The 2004 reform of the Mathematics syllabus, following calls that it was too hard, attracted criticism.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] In the change, content consisting of three modules (Pure 1–3) was spread to four modules (Core 1–4).
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] It was alleged that this made the course easier as students did less work for the same qualifications.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] Further reforms in 2006 to make the Mathematics syllabus more popular were met with mixed opinions.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] Supporters cited it would reverse the downward trend in students taking the subject whilst others were concerned that the subject was "still incredibly difficult".
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] Examples of concerns were those raised in 2009 by Sir Mike Rake, Chairman of BT Group, Sir Terry Leahy, Chairman of Tesco and by Sir Christopher Gent, Chairman of GlaxoSmithKline.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] Some schools have also moved to offering the Cambridge Pre-U as an alternative to A-levels and with higher tariffs.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] With increased modularisation of subjects, the amount of time that young adults are spending being examined in the UK has risen considerably.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] It was estimated in a report by educationalists that by the age of 19 children will have spent an entire year of their school education being assessed.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] As a result of such criticisms about the "burden of assessment", since candidates have taken four papers for most A-levels, instead of six as in the past.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] This means that there are two modules for AS and two more for A2 for the majority of A-levels.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] However, this will not be the case for all A-levels: Biology, Human Biology, Chemistry, Physics, Electronics, Geology, Music, Welsh and Science will continue with six units, three units for AS and A2 respectively, and 600 UMS for the A-level.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] Mathematics (including Further Mathematics, Additional Further Mathematics, Statistics, and the Use of Mathematics AS), will not change structurally in the modular reform; it will stay on 600 UMS (300 UMS for AS), but it will include the new A* grade and the 'Stretch and Challenge' provision.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] Also, Bengali, Modern Hebrew, Punjabi, Polish, Arabic, Japanese, Modern Greek, Biblical Hebrew, Dutch, Gujarati, Persian, Portuguese, and Turkish will remain at two units, one for AS and one for A2.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] However, they will move to 200 UMS for A-level.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] Chinese will also move to 200 UMS, but instead of two units, it will move to three units: AS will have two units, A2 will have one.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] It is the first A-level to have an odd number of units since Curriculum 2000.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] Cambridge University has warned that it is extremely unlikely that it will accept applicants who are taking two or more supposedly 'softer' A-level subjects out of 3.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] It has outlined a list of subjects it considers to be 'unsuitable', which includes Accounting, Design and Technology, Film Studies, Information and Communication Technology, Media Studies, Photography, and Sports studies.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] As a result of dislike of the modular system, many schools now offer the alternative International Baccalaureate Diploma qualification.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] The course offers more subjects, extracurricular activity, a philosophical epistemological component known as "Theory of Knowledge", as well as the requirement of an extended essay on any subject of a candidate's choice.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] Unlike the current AS/A2 system, the International Baccalaureate is not based on a modular system.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] The Diploma Programme, administered by the International Baccalaureate, is a recognised pre-university educational programme.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] Former British Prime Minister Tony Blair suggested in 2013 that one state school in every county should offer the International Baccalaureate Diploma Programme as an alternative to A-levels.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] Maths, Chemistry, or Biology), a language subject (e.g.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] English Language, English Literature, French, German, Spanish), and a "creative" subject (e.g.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] Art Studies)—in many cases students choose three closely linked subjects—for example, Mathematics, Physics and Chemistry or Sociology, Psychology, and Politics.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] This is in part due to university entrance requirements, which, for degree programs such as medicine, may require three related A-level subjects, but non-traditional combinations are becoming more common ("British Council Australia Education UK").
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] Thus, while the purpose of Curriculum 2000 was to encourage students to undertake contrasting subjects, to broaden their 'skill-base', there is a tendency to pursue similar disciplines.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] However, others disagree, arguing that the additional AS-level(s) studied would already have provided more breadth compared with the old system.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] Students applying to universities before receiving their A-level results typically do so on the basis of predicted grades, which are issued by schools and colleges.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] A student's predicted grades usually depend on their GCSE results, performance throughout the course, performance in tests and mock examinations, or a combination of these factors.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] A possible reformation would be something called the post-qualifications applications system (PQA), where applicants apply to university after they receive their results.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] It has been argued that this would be fairer to applicants, especially those from lower-income families whose results were thought to be under-predicted.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] However, a more recent UCAS report shows that although the reliability of predicted grades declines in step with family income, this can still lead to an over-prediction effect for lower income groups.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] Just 45% of predicted grades are accurate – 47% are over-predictions and 9% under-predictions.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] A recent UCAS consultation rejected the implementation of PQA following opposition from universities, schools and awarding bodies.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] In 2020 the A-level system was challenged by the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] Ofqual advised that the 2020 A-level exams should be cancelled, students be given a completion certificate, and universities widen the intake relying on a higher drop-out.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] The government intervened and grades were to be awarded using an algorithm.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] There was a public outcry, explained Roger Taylor the former chair of Ofqual who resigned.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] It was a “colossal error of judgment”: awarding grades calculated by algorithm was not acceptable to the public.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] Instead the final grades were awarded by teacher assessment, a system that was repeated in 2021.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] Taylor explained the algorithm was robust, it was the way it was being used that caused the problem: that was down to human decisions.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level-united-kingdom] Researchers from the London School of Economics and University College London researchers showed that teacher assessment gave a 15% advantage to students with graduate parents.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level] They were introduced in England, Wales and Northern Ireland in 1951 to replace the Higher School Certificate.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level] The A-level permits students to have potential access to a chosen university they applied to with UCAS points.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level] They could be accepted into it should they meet the requirements of the university.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level] A number of Commonwealth countries have developed qualifications with the same name as and a similar format to the British A-levels.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level] Obtaining an A-level, or equivalent qualifications, is generally required across the board for university entrance, with universities granting offers based on grades achieved.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level] A-levels are typically worked towards over two years.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level] Normally, students take three or four A-level courses in their first year of sixth form, and most taking four cut back to three in their second year.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level] This is because university offers are normally based on three A-level grades, and taking a fourth can have an impact on grades.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level] Unlike other level-3 qualifications, such as the International Baccalaureate, A-levels have no specific subject requirements, so students have the opportunity to combine any subjects they wish to take.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level] However, students normally pick their courses based on the degree they wish to pursue at university: most degrees require specific A-levels for entry.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level] The second part is known as an A2 or A2-level, which is generally more in-depth and academically rigorous than the AS.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level] The AS and A2 marks are combined for a full A-level award.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level] The A2-level is not a qualification on its own and must be accompanied by an AS-level in the same subject for certification.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level] A-level exams are a matriculation examination and can be compared to *matura*, the *Abitur*, the *Baccalauréat* or the Bagrut certificate.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level] Several countries use A-levels as a school-leaving qualification.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level] However, A levels are mainly taken in the UK.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level] The A-levels taken by students in other countries may differ from the A-levels taken in the United Kingdom.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level] Many schools in countries world-wide offer A-Levels through international cross-border exam boards, which include Cambridge International Education (CIE), Pearson Edexcel, Learning Resource Network (LRN) and OxfordAQA.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level] A-levels are a college or sixth form leaving qualification offered in England, Wales, and Northern Ireland.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level] In Scotland, A-levels are also offered by some schools as an alternative school-leaving qualification in place of the Scottish Advanced Higher.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level] Oxford AQA, Edexcel, Cambridge International Education (CIE), and Learning Resource Network (LRN) also offer international versions of the British A-levels in the United Kingdom and worldwide.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level] The British variant of A/AS-levels is also taken in many Commonwealth and former Commonwealth countries, as well as in examination centers worldwide.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level] British international schools in foreign countries generally offer the British A-levels as offered through Edexcel or Cambridge International Examinations.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level] At select examination centers, the British A-level exams may also be available to private candidates.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level] In Bangladesh, the GCE AS and A-level are offered by Cambridge International Education (CIE) and Pearson Edexcel after completion of IGCSE (CIE or Pearson Edexcel) or Cambridge O-Level, and is conducted by the British Council.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level] GCE Advanced Level qualifications are offered by some of the private, public, and international schools as an alternative to HSC (Higher Secondary School Certificate) offered by the Government Board of Education.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level] It has become a popular choice among students, but due to financial implications, its reach is limited to the middle and upper classes in major cities such as Dhaka and Chittagong.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level] In Brunei, the A-level qualification is offered, with examinations conducted by Cambridge International Education (CIE).
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level] Some subjects are unique to Brunei or have a format, curriculum, or syllabus that is unique to Brunei.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level] The Advanced Level of Cameroon is based on the Cambridge International Education and similarly, conducted by the government of Cameroon in collaboration with Cambridge University.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level] All the courses taken are related to what the candidate is willing to pursue a career in university and these courses are on a recognizable international standard for university entrance; as they are major relevant courses.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level] The British A-level qualifications such as GCE A-level and International A-level are widely accepted in Hong Kong as an alternative to the Hong Kong Diploma of Secondary Education for both admission and employment purposes.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level] It is one of the most popular qualifications used for university admission via the non-JUPAS channel.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level] For example, average non-JUPAS offers from the Hong Kong University of Science and Technology require one to three A*s (the mid-50% range).
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level] Since the introduction of the high distinction grade (A*) in 2010, the British A-level examination has regained its power to differentiate the very top levels of ability.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level] According to the British Department for Education, in the academic year 2014/15, approximately 7.3%, 2.7%, 1.0%, and 0.3% of all the candidates from the GCSE cohort (548,480) achieved one to four A*s or a better result in the GCE A-level examination.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level] This percentile rank is one important input for equating the levels in both examinations.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level] On the sole basis of percentile ranks and the grade statistics from HKEAA in 2017, a score of 29/35 from the best five subjects in Hong Kong Diploma of Secondary Education is comparable to 1A*2A in the best three British A-levels, 32/35 to 2A*1A, 33/35 to 3A* and 34/35 to 4A*.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level] Relevant authorities such as the Hong Kong Examination and Assessment Authority (HKEAA) and UCAS also sought to connect the results from both exam systems to open doors for the holders of these qualifications who wish to study locally or overseas.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level] Officially, the top distinction levels, A* in A-level and 5** in HKDSE, are currently recognized as broadly equivalent.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level] In India, Cambridge International Education (CIE), and Learning Resource Network (LRN) GCE Advanced Level qualifications are offered at private and international schools as an alternative to the conventional Higher Secondary Certificate (HSC).
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level] The International A-Level qualifications are offered in some private schools and international schools which teaching medium is English and adopt IAL curriculum.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level] Students in Macau can take the Cambridge International Education (CIE) or Edexcel International A-Level offered at their school.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level] It is one of the most popular qualifications for the students who want to pursue their university study in UK, Hong Kong, Australia, and New Zealand.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level] International Advanced Level qualification is also accepted by Macau local universities for applying for direct admission, the applicants with IAL qualification are not required to take the Joint Admission Examination for Macao Four Higher Education Institutions.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level] In Malaysia, the A-level qualification is offered, with examinations conducted by Cambridge International Education (CIE) and Learning Resource Network.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level] Some subjects are unique to Malaysia or have a format, curriculum, or syllabus that is unique to Malaysia.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level] For instance, there are two types of A-level in Malaysia, Cambridge A-level (administered by Cambridge International Examinations) and Edexcel International Advanced Level (administered by Pearson Edexcel).
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level] Some exam papers offered, such as French, are customized to support the national educational standards.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level] Additionally, International A-level qualifications from Edexcel are available, for which exams may be registered through the Mauritius Examinations Syndicate.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level] In Nepal, A-level offered from Cambridge International Education (CIE) is the most popular and is presented by several public, private, and international institutions as an alternative to the National Examination Board's 10+2 curriculum.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level] A-level has become a popular choice for many students in Nepal.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level] Besides A-level, International Baccalaureate and Advanced Placement are also offered at this level.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level] Nepali students generally appear for 4 subjects at A-level and 5 at AS-level.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level] A-levels are offered in Pakistan by governmental and private institutions, along with International Baccalaureate and other international examinations like the Advanced Placement though A levels is by far the most popular.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level] Examinations are handled by international British boards and the program is equivalent to Higher Secondary School Certificate.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level] Cram Schools are established all around the country which prepares the students to take the examinations as private candidates.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level] In Seychelles, the A-level qualification is offered, with examinations conducted by Cambridge International Education (CIE).
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level] Some subjects are unique to Seychelles or have a format, curriculum, or syllabus that is unique to Seychelles.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level] In Singapore, H1/H2/H3 level qualifications are awarded upon successful completion of examinations jointly administered by Singapore Ministry of Education (MOE), Singapore Examinations and Assessment Board (SEAB) and Cambridge International Education (CIE).
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level] In Sri Lanka, A-level qualifications are offered by governmental and non-governmental schools (Private Schools).
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level] The qualifications are awarded upon successful completion of examinations called Local A-levels while most of the private schools award them upon London A-levels.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level] Local GCE Advanced Level qualifications are offered by the Department of Examinations.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level] Passing A-levels is a major requirement for applying to local universities and for private universities in Sri Lanka.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level] In the recent past, Universities in Sri Lanka have given the opportunity to apply for their foundation courses which only require O-level (Ordinary Level) results.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level] A-level is an education structure after the completion of 11 years of Universal Primary Education (UPE).
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level] Universal Primary Education consists of two levels, the primary school level of seven years and ordinarily secondary level, of four years.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level] Students are then required to sit for the National Examination which is done on a specific month in a certain year.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level] The exams are done throughout the country on the same date provided by the examination board.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level] Examinations will depend on the cluster and core subjects in which a student shall take.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level] There are three major clusters, namely science, business, and liberal arts plus core subjects of which are seven in total or more.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level] Students who will then pass according to the National Examination Standards shall be selected to join Advanced Secondary Education and are selected according to the subjects they passed the most and by their will to pursue certain subjects.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level] There are only three core subjects to study in Advanced Level and one or more optional subjects to sit for the Advanced Certificate of Secondary Education Examination (ACSEE).
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level] Then students are awarded Advanced Certificate of Secondary Education only if they have passed.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level] The pass marks are arranged according to grades and the grades will determine whether a student will qualify to join tertiary education.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level] A-level education is a two years education which is offered by the government and non-government schools.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level] In Uganda, a Uganda Advanced Certificate of Education is awarded to students who have passed their national examinations that are set and marked by the Uganda National Examination Board (UNEB).
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level] It is among the requirements for one to join a university in Uganda.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level] The advanced level takes two years for one to complete.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level] Some international schools in Uganda also offer A-level courses from Cambridge and Edexcel.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level] The GCE Advanced Level qualification is offered by the Zimbabwe School Examinations Council (ZIMSEC).
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level] Before, this qualification was jointly offered by Cambridge International Education and the Council in Zimbabwe.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level] Although exam boards often alter their curricula, this table shows the majority of subjects that are consistently available for study.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level] Between 2015 and 2018 (first assessment Summer 2017), A-levels in England were reformed, transitioning from a modular to linear structure (initially across 13 subjects).
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level] This means all A-level exams are taken in one sitting as a set of terminal exams (three exams for the majority of subjects), and there is no coursework set for many subjects.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level] For A-levels that retain a coursework element, the percentage of the final grade determined by coursework has been reduced.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level] An example of this can be seen in Edexcel's new English Literature A-level, reformed in 2015, which reduces the amount of coursework to 20% (from 40% in the old modular specification).
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level] A-levels are no longer separated into units, and students must resit all of their exams if they wish to resit the qualification.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level] While these reforms were expected to be complete for first teaching in 2017, this was extended to 2018 to include the reforms of less common languages such as Modern Hebrew and Bengali.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level] The AS-level is now a separate qualification and is not required for an A-level award, although it still encompasses the first year of the full A-level content.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level] However, unlike AS-levels in the old modular courses, they are now worth only 40% as many UCAS points as a full A-level (from 50% in the modular courses), as content from the second year of A-level is considered more academically challenging than that of the first year.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level] As these reforms took place in stages, many students took a combination of modular and linear courses before all reforms were complete, with AS-levels still being part of an A-level in older modular courses.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level] These reforms look to combat grade inflation, where the proportion of students achieving the highest grades increases year upon year, causing the value of those grades to be eroded.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level] The modular system has also been criticised for nurturing a 'resit culture', while new linear courses give no opportunity to resit individual units.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level] Controversially, some A-level course subjects have been abolished since 2017 as part of these reforms.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level] These include archaeology, anthropology, creative writing, general studies, and home economics.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level] Many universities criticised the scrapping of exams taken at the end of AS-level, which used to be worth 50% of the overall A-level grade.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level] This is because the universities used the grades achieved at AS-level (available to universities after a student applies during the second year of A-levels) as an indication of a student's ability and thus whether to give said student an offer.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level] Opposition to these reforms in Wales and Northern Ireland has resulted in maintaining the modular structure of their qualification.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level] In September 2023, it was announced by Prime Minister Rishi Sunak that the A-level would be scrapped in England and merged with T-levels to form the Advanced British Standard, however this was cancelled by the Labour government after the 2024 general election.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level] In 2002, schools in the Caribbean began to move away from the GCE Advanced Level to the CXC CAPE examinations, making them a de facto university entrance examination.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level] Some universities also require applicants to take separate entrance examinations.
[src:university-of-oxford/a-level] The International Baccalaureate and European Baccalaureate are also accepted.
[src:university-of-oxford/abertay-university] Abertay launched the world's first computer games degree in 1997 and in 2017 held a programme of events celebrating 20 Years of Games.
[src:university-of-oxford/abertay-university] Abertay was also the first to offer a degree in Ethical Hacking, starting in 2006.
[src:university-of-oxford/abertay-university] In 1872 Sir David Baxter, 1st Baronet of Kilmaron, died and bequeathed £20,000 (£1.96 million adjusting for inflation) for the establishment of a mechanics' institute in Dundee.
[src:university-of-oxford/abertay-university] The Baxter bequest was intended to create an educational establishment permitting young male working mechanics and other craftsmen to better themselves.
[src:university-of-oxford/abertay-university] After some years of delay the trustees finalised a scheme and met the conditions of the bequest and the Dundee Technical Institute opened on 15 October 1888 in grounds, purchased from University College, Dundee, adjacent to Small's Wynd, Dundee.
[src:university-of-oxford/abertay-university] In 1901 the Dundee Technical Institute enrolled 723 part-time students and was one of the first education hubs to be recognised as a 'central institution' by the Scotch Education Department.
[src:university-of-oxford/abertay-university] In 1906 a new site in Bell Street, Dundee was purchased to build a larger complex to accommodate a growing student population.
[src:university-of-oxford/abertay-university] In 1911 the completed complex was formally opened as the Dundee Technical College & School of Art.
[src:university-of-oxford/abertay-university] In 1909 James Duncan of Jordanstone left £60,000 (£6.17 million adjusting for inflation) to establish an art college in Dundee.
[src:university-of-oxford/abertay-university] The college of art became a formally separate institution, known as the Duncan of Jordanstone College of Art and Design, in 1975, remaining independent until 1994 when it became part of the University of Dundee.
[src:university-of-oxford/abertay-university] The First World War reduced enrolments and growth but the vocational nature of the institute meant that its classes were relevant to the war effort.
[src:university-of-oxford/abertay-university] The first women students enrolled in 1914.
[src:university-of-oxford/abertay-university] After the Second World War enrolments and the scope of delivery continued to expand, as did the reputation of the institute.
[src:university-of-oxford/abertay-university] By 1951 the institute was teaching courses that led to examinations for the external degrees of the University of London in pharmacy, mechanical, civil, and electrical engineering.
[src:university-of-oxford/abertay-university] In 1955 the National Council for Technological Awards was established and validated diplomas in technology which were equivalent in standard if not in name to honours degrees.
[src:university-of-oxford/abertay-university] The institution began offering degrees itself in 1956.
[src:university-of-oxford/abertay-university] Abertay University was created in 1994, under the Further and Higher Education Act 1992, granting the title "University of Abertay Dundee" to the Dundee Institute of Technology.
[src:university-of-oxford/abertay-university] Since 2014 the university has promoted itself as Abertay University.
[src:university-of-oxford/abertay-university] The university's name was formally changed to Abertay University by an Order of Council on 1 September 2019.
[src:university-of-oxford/abertay-university] Abertay was the first university in the world to offer a "computer games" degree in 1997.
[src:university-of-oxford/abertay-university] Abertay was the UK's first university to be recognised as a Centre for Excellence in Computer Games Education, and is associated with a business support programme for computer game startups.
[src:university-of-oxford/abertay-university] Abertay University is situated in the centre of Dundee.
[src:university-of-oxford/abertay-university] The campus buildings include the historic Old College buildings of Dundee Business School, the Bernard King Library, and others.
[src:university-of-oxford/abertay-university] The Bernard King Library in Bell Street opened to learners in February 1998 and was formally opened by Queen Elizabeth II on 30 June 1998.
[src:university-of-oxford/abertay-university] The library was voted best new building in Scotland in the 1998 Scottish Design Awards competition.
[src:university-of-oxford/abertay-university] The Abertay cyberQuarter opened in June 2022 with they key aim of bringing together students, academics, and organisations to help solve global cybersecurity challenges.
[src:university-of-oxford/abertay-university] The centre offers a physical space for collaboration and experimentation using digital tools and technologies.
[src:university-of-oxford/abertay-university] Abertay is a small university that receives the majority of its funding for teaching rather than research.
[src:university-of-oxford/abertay-university] Nevertheless, according to the results of the Research Excellence Framework 2014 (REF2014), Abertay was the highest ranked modern university in Scotland for 'research intensity'.
[src:university-of-oxford/abertay-university] The university submitted an increased proportion of staff in REF2014 compared to RAE2008 and achieved an average score of 2.15 – which in REF terms means "quality that is recognised internationally in terms of originality, significance, and rigour".
[src:university-of-oxford/abertay-university] This was an improvement from the average score of 1.83, "national recognition", achieved in RAE2008.
[src:university-of-oxford/abertay-university] The Research Excellence Framework 2021 (REF2021) published on 12 May 2022 and Abertay recorded a 23% increase in research that is "internationally excellent" or "world-leading" since the last REF in 2014.
[src:university-of-oxford/abertay-university] In 2009 it established the UK's first Centre for Excellence in Computer Games Education, and a business support programme.
[src:university-of-oxford/abertay-university] Abertay runs five of the 25 interactive and games degree courses accredited in the UK by Creative Skillset, the industry skills body for the creative sector, more than any other institution.
[src:university-of-oxford/abertay-university] The university was established by a statutory instrument The University of Abertay Dundee (Scotland) Order of Council 1994.
[src:university-of-oxford/abertay-university] The order sets out the objects of the university and the general functions of the University Court to 'conduct the affairs of the university and carry out and promote its objects'.
[src:university-of-oxford/abertay-university] Abertay was the UK's first University to be recognised as a Centre for Excellence in Computer Games Education.
[src:university-of-oxford/abertay-university] The Centre for Excellence is accredited by Skillset and has strong links with industrial partners from across the broadcast, interactive and wider digital media sectors.
[src:university-of-oxford/abertay-university] These partners include BBC Scotland, BBC Vision, BSkyB, Channel 4, Electronic Arts, Codemasters, Blitz Games Studios, Rare, Sony Computer Entertainment Europe, Microsoft and Disney Interactive.
[src:university-of-oxford/abertay-university] Abertay was the first university in the world to have a degree in Ethical Hacking, differentiating from its other cyber-security degree counterparts by taking a more offensive approach to security.
[src:university-of-oxford/abertay-university] The university began to offer this degree in 2006.
[src:university-of-oxford/abertay-university] In 2020 the university was one of eight in the UK, and the only one in Scotland, to be named an Academic Centre of Excellence in Cybersecurity by the National Cybersecurity Centre.
[src:university-of-oxford/abertay-university] The university is also home to the Ethical Hacking society, which hosts the Securi-Tay conference, the largest student-run security conference in Europe.
[src:university-of-oxford/abertay-university] Abertay provides a range of short courses that provide the public with opportunities to improve current skills and enhance knowledge in several areas including digital marketing and sustainability.
[src:university-of-oxford/abertay-university] Fully funded by the Scottish Funding Council, the courses are free to applicants.
[src:university-of-oxford/abertay-university] Each short course is credit-bearing and a recognised university qualification.
[src:university-of-oxford/abertay-university] Prior to 1953 no coat of arms was registered in the name of the college.
[src:university-of-oxford/abertay-university] The original Ensigns Armorial were recorded in the Public Register of All Arms and Bearings in Scotland on 25 July 1953, in the name of Dundee Technical College.
[src:university-of-oxford/abertay-university] They were subsequently transferred to Dundee College of Technology in 1977, then to Dundee Institute of Technology in 1988 and, finally, to the University of Abertay Dundee on 25 April 1994.
[src:university-of-oxford/abertay-university] The top left sector is taken from the arms of Sir David Baxter of Kilmaron, who bequeathed a significant sum of money in order to establish the original Dundee Technical Institute in 1888.
[src:university-of-oxford/abertay-university] The top right sector is taken from the arms of Sir William Dalgleish, who was the senior trustee of what by then was known as Dundee Technical College and School of Art, and who opened the first building – Old College – on Abertay's present campus on Bell Street in 1911.
[src:university-of-oxford/abertay-university] The top middle sector of three chevrons is the heraldic symbol for "technical".
[src:university-of-oxford/abertay-university] The pot of lilies in base is taken from the arms of the City of Dundee, with the books on either side representing education.
[src:university-of-oxford/abertay-university] Aaron McCauley, a graduate of Abertay, designed and registered the Abertay tartan in 2003.
[src:university-of-oxford/abertay-university] The tartan is based on Abertay's promotional colours of dark blue, red, gold and green from its coat of arms.
[src:university-of-oxford/abertay-university] The Abertay Students' Association (Abertay SA) is based in the ground floor of the Bernard King library building.
[src:university-of-oxford/abertay-university] Abertay SA co-ordinates all societies and acts as the voice and representation of all of Abertay's students.
[src:university-of-oxford/abertay-university] Abertay University has a wide group of sports teams competing under the university banner.
[src:university-of-oxford/abertay-university] It ranges from Tennis to Hockey who compete in the BUCS (British Universities & Colleges Sport) leagues, which competes against other universities and colleges in Scotland.
[src:university-of-oxford/abertay-university] The Football, Hockey and Basketball teams have their 1st teams competing in the highest league (BUCS 1A).
[src:university-of-oxford/abertay-university] The university has a fierce rivalry with Dundee University, competing in a yearly Varsity competition.
[src:university-of-oxford/aberystwyth-university] Founded in 1872 as **University College Wales, Aberystwyth**, it became a founder member of the University of Wales in 1894, and changed its name to the **University College of Wales, Aberystwyth**.
[src:university-of-oxford/aberystwyth-university] In the mid-1990s, the university again changed its name to become the **University of Wales, Aberystwyth**.
[src:university-of-oxford/aberystwyth-university] On 1 September 2007, the University of Wales ceased to be a federal university and Aberystwyth University became independent again.
[src:university-of-oxford/aberystwyth-university] The annual income of the institution for 2024–2025 was £124.8 million of which £19.2 million was from research grants and contracts, with an expenditure of £130.3 million.
[src:university-of-oxford/aberystwyth-university] In the middle of the 19th century, eminent Welsh people were advocating the establishment of a university in the principality of Wales.
[src:university-of-oxford/aberystwyth-university] One of these, Thomas Nicholas, whose book, *Middle and High Class Schools, and University Education for Wales* (1863), is said to have "exerted great influence on educated Welshmen".
[src:university-of-oxford/aberystwyth-university] Funded through public and private subscriptions, and with five regional committees (London, Manchester, Liverpool, North and South Wales) guaranteeing funds for the first three years' running costs, the university opened in October 1872 with 26 students.
[src:university-of-oxford/aberystwyth-university] Thomas Charles Edwards was the principal.
[src:university-of-oxford/aberystwyth-university] In October 1875, chapels in Wales raised the next tranche of funds from over 70,000 contributors.
[src:university-of-oxford/aberystwyth-university] Until 1893, when the college joined the University of Wales as a founder member, students applying to Aberystwyth sat the University of London's entrance exams.
[src:university-of-oxford/aberystwyth-university] In 1885, a fire damaged what is now known as the Old College, Aberystwyth, and in 1897 the first 14 acres of what became the main Penglais campus were purchased.
[src:university-of-oxford/aberystwyth-university] Incorporated by royal charter in 1893, the university installed Albert Edward, Prince of Wales, as chancellor in 1896, the same year it awarded an honorary degree to the former British prime minister, William Gladstone.
[src:university-of-oxford/aberystwyth-university] The university's coat of arms dates from the 1880s.
[src:university-of-oxford/aberystwyth-university] The shield features two red dragons to symbolise Wales, and an open book to symbolise learning.
[src:university-of-oxford/aberystwyth-university] The crest, an eagle or phoenix above a flaming tower, may signify the college's rebirth after the 1885 fire.
[src:university-of-oxford/aberystwyth-university] The motto is *Nid Byd, Byd Heb Wybodaeth* ('a world without knowledge is no world at all').
[src:university-of-oxford/aberystwyth-university] In the early 1900s, the university added courses that included law, applied mathematics, pure mathematics and botany.
[src:university-of-oxford/aberystwyth-university] The Department for International Politics, which Aberystwyth says is the oldest such department in the world, was founded in 1919.
[src:university-of-oxford/aberystwyth-university] By 1977, the university's staff included eight Fellows of the Royal Society, such as Gwendolen Rees, the first Welsh woman to be elected an FRS.
[src:university-of-oxford/aberystwyth-university] The Department of Sports and Exercise Science was established in 2000.
[src:university-of-oxford/aberystwyth-university] Joint honours psychology degrees were introduced in September 2007, and single honours psychology in 2009.
[src:university-of-oxford/aberystwyth-university] The chancellor of the university is Dame Nicola Davies, who took up the position in January 2025.
[src:university-of-oxford/aberystwyth-university] The visitor of the university is an appointment made by the privy council, under the royal charter of the university.
[src:university-of-oxford/aberystwyth-university] Since July 2014, the holder of this office is Sir Roderick Evans.
[src:university-of-oxford/aberystwyth-university] In 2011, the university appointed a new vice chancellor under whom the academic departments were restructured as larger subject-themed institutes.
[src:university-of-oxford/aberystwyth-university] In 2022, the university celebrated its 150th anniversary, being established in 1872 (known at the time as The University College of Wales).
[src:university-of-oxford/aberystwyth-university] The Institute of Biological, Environmental and Rural Sciences (IBERS) is a research and teaching centre which brings together staff from the Institutes of Rural Sciences and Biological Sciences and the Institute of Grassland and Environmental Research (IGER).
[src:university-of-oxford/aberystwyth-university] Around 360 research, teaching and support staff conduct basic, strategic and applied research in biology.
[src:university-of-oxford/aberystwyth-university] The institute is located in two areas; one at the main teaching Penglais campus and another rural research hub at the Gogerddan campus.
[src:university-of-oxford/aberystwyth-university] In 1998, the Department of Economics (founded in 1912), the Department of Accounting and Finance (founded in 1979) and the Centre for Business Studies merged to create the School of Management and Business.
[src:university-of-oxford/aberystwyth-university] In 2013, the School joined the Department of Information Studies and the Department of Law and Criminology at a new campus at Llanbadarn Fawr.
[src:university-of-oxford/aberystwyth-university] The school was shortlisted for "Business School of the Year" in the *Times Higher Education* Awards (2014).
[src:university-of-oxford/aberystwyth-university] In 2016, the institute, minus the Department of Information Studies, was renamed the Institute of Business and Law, the remaining departments being renamed Aberystwyth Business School and Aberystwyth Law School.
[src:university-of-oxford/aberystwyth-university] The Department of Computer Science (founded in 1970), conducts research in automated reasoning, computational biology, vision graphics and visualisation and intelligent robotics.
[src:university-of-oxford/aberystwyth-university] AberMUD, the first popular internet-based MUD, was written in the department by then-student Alan Cox.
[src:university-of-oxford/aberystwyth-university] Jan Pinkava, another graduate, won an Oscar for his short animated film *Geri's Game*.
[src:university-of-oxford/aberystwyth-university] The Department of Geography and Earth Sciences (IGES) was formed, in 1989, from the former Departments of Geography (established in 1918) and Geology.
[src:university-of-oxford/aberystwyth-university] Bowen map library, containing 80,000 maps and 500 atlases.
[src:university-of-oxford/aberystwyth-university] The College of Librarianship Wales (CLW) was established at Llanbadarn Fawr in 1964, in response to a recommendation for the training of bilingual librarians that was made in the Bourdillon Report on *Standards of public library service in England* (HMSO, 1962).
[src:university-of-oxford/aberystwyth-university] The college grew rapidly, developing close links to the Welsh speaking and professional communities, acquiring an international reputation and pioneering flexible and distance learning courses.
[src:university-of-oxford/aberystwyth-university] It claimed to be Europe's largest institution for training librarians.
[src:university-of-oxford/aberystwyth-university] The independent college merged with the university in August 1989 and the department moved to the Penglais campus a quarter of a century later.
[src:university-of-oxford/aberystwyth-university] Following the merger, the new department took over responsibility for existing offerings in archives administration and modern records management.
[src:university-of-oxford/aberystwyth-university] The Department of International Politics is the oldest of its kind in the world.
[src:university-of-oxford/aberystwyth-university] It was founded, shortly after the First World War in 1919, with the stated purpose of furthering political understanding of the world in the hope of avoiding such conflicts in the future.
[src:university-of-oxford/aberystwyth-university] This goal led to the creation of the Woodrow Wilson Chair of International Politics, with Wilson having played a significant role in its creation.
[src:university-of-oxford/aberystwyth-university] The department has over 700 students from 40 countries studying at undergraduate, masters and PhD levels.
[src:university-of-oxford/aberystwyth-university] It achieved a 95% score for student satisfaction in the 2016 National Student Survey, placing it as the highest-ranking politics department in Wales and within the UK's top ten.
[src:university-of-oxford/aberystwyth-university] The department has hosted notable academic staff in the field including E.
[src:university-of-oxford/aberystwyth-university] Carr, Leopold Kohr, Andrew Linklater, Ken Booth, Steve Smith, Michael Cox, Michael MccGwire, Jenny Edkins and Colin J.
[src:university-of-oxford/aberystwyth-university] The Department of Law and Criminology (founded in 1901) is housed in the Hugh Owen Building on the Penglais campus, and includes the *Centre for Welsh Legal Affairs*, a specialist research centre.
[src:university-of-oxford/aberystwyth-university] All academic staff are engaged in research, and the *International Journal of Biosciences and the Law* and the *Cambrian Law Review* are edited in the department.
[src:university-of-oxford/aberystwyth-university] In 2013, the department joined the Department of Information Studies and the School of Management and Business at a new campus at Llanbadarn Fawr, as part of a newly created Institute of Management, Law and Information Studies.
[src:university-of-oxford/aberystwyth-university] In September 2018, the department moved back to the Hugh Owen Building, based in the Penglais campus, and its name changed from Aberystwyth Law School to the Department of Law and Criminology.
[src:university-of-oxford/aberystwyth-university] Aberystwyth has taught modern languages since 1874.
[src:university-of-oxford/aberystwyth-university] French, German, Italian and Spanish courses are taught at both beginners' and advanced levels, in a research-active academic environment.
[src:university-of-oxford/aberystwyth-university] One of its research projects is the *Anglo-Norman Dictionary*, based in Aberystwyth since 2001 and available online since 2005.
[src:university-of-oxford/aberystwyth-university] Physics was first taught at Aberystwyth as part of Natural Philosophy, Astronomy and Mathematics under N.
[src:university-of-oxford/aberystwyth-university] Grimley, soon after the foundation of the University College.
[src:university-of-oxford/aberystwyth-university] It became a department in 1877, under the leadership of F.
[src:university-of-oxford/aberystwyth-university] The department was located in the south wing of what is now the Old College, but later moved to the Physics Building on the Penglais Campus.
[src:university-of-oxford/aberystwyth-university] The first chair in Physics was offered to D.
[src:university-of-oxford/aberystwyth-university] Before the First World War, much of the early research in the department was undertaken in Germany.
[src:university-of-oxford/aberystwyth-university] Early research in the 1900s was concerned with electrical conductivity and quantum theory, later moving into thermal conductivity and acoustics.
[src:university-of-oxford/aberystwyth-university] In 1931, the department hosted the Faraday Centenary Exhibition.
[src:university-of-oxford/aberystwyth-university] Williams was appointed to the Chair of Physics in 1938 where he continued his research into sub-atomic particles using a cloud chamber.
[src:university-of-oxford/aberystwyth-university] Following the Second World War, research was concerned with mechanical and nuclear physics, later moving into the fields of air density, experimental rocket launching equipment and radar.
[src:university-of-oxford/aberystwyth-university] In 2007, Aberystwyth established psychology as a "Centre for Applied Psychology" within the Department of International Politics.
[src:university-of-oxford/aberystwyth-university] By 2011, psychology had moved into its current premises in Penbryn 5 on the Penglais Campus.
[src:university-of-oxford/aberystwyth-university] The department has over 550 undergraduate students, with degrees accredited by the British Psychological Society and is home to an MSc in Behaviour Change.
[src:university-of-oxford/aberystwyth-university] The main campus of the university is situated on Penglais Hill, overlooking the town of Aberystwyth and Cardigan Bay, and comprises most of the university buildings, Arts Centre, Students' Union, and many of the student residences.
[src:university-of-oxford/aberystwyth-university] Just below Penglais Campus is the National Library of Wales, one of Britain's five legal deposit libraries.
[src:university-of-oxford/aberystwyth-university] The landscaping of the Penglais Campus is historically significant and is listed at Grade II* on the Cadw/ICOMOS Register of Parks and Gardens of Special Historic Interest in Wales.
[src:university-of-oxford/aberystwyth-university] The Llanbadarn Centre is located approximately one mile to the east of the Penglais Campus, near Llanbadarn Fawr, overlooking the town and Cardigan Bay to the west, with the backdrop of the Cambrian Mountains to the east.
[src:university-of-oxford/aberystwyth-university] Llanbadarn Centre hosted Aberystwyth Law School and Aberystwyth Business School, which together formed the Institute of Business and Law.
[src:university-of-oxford/aberystwyth-university] The Department of Information Studies is also based there.
[src:university-of-oxford/aberystwyth-university] Additionally, the Llanbadarn Campus is the site of the Aberystwyth branch of Coleg Ceredigion (a further education college, and not part of the university).
[src:university-of-oxford/aberystwyth-university] At Gogerddan, on the outskirts of town is located the university's major centre for research in land based sciences and the main centre for the Institute of Biological, Environmental and Rural Science.
[src:university-of-oxford/aberystwyth-university] The School of Art is located between the Penglais Campus and the centre of Aberystwyth, in what was originally the Edward Davies Memorial Chemistry Laboratories.
[src:university-of-oxford/aberystwyth-university] A listed building, the Edward Davies Building is one of the finest examples of architecture in Aberystwyth.
[src:university-of-oxford/aberystwyth-university] The site of the original university is the Old College, currently the subject of the "New Life for Old College" project which aims to transform it into an integrated centre of heritage, culture, learning and knowledge exchange.
[src:university-of-oxford/aberystwyth-university] The university opened an international campus in Mauritius in 2015 operating as *Aberystwyth University (Mauritian Branch Campus)* and registered with the Tertiary Education Commission of Mauritius, but closed it to new enrolments two years later due to low enrolment numbers.
[src:university-of-oxford/aberystwyth-university] Less than 200 students enrolled with the Mauritius campus, which had the capacity for 2,000 students, before its 2018 closure and the university lost more than a million pounds as a result of the venture.
[src:university-of-oxford/aberystwyth-university] Most of the student residences are on campus, with the rest in walking distance of the campus and Aberystwyth town centre.
[src:university-of-oxford/aberystwyth-university] Accommodation ranges from "traditional" catered residences to en-suite self-catered accommodation, and from budget rooms to more luxurious studio apartments.
[src:university-of-oxford/aberystwyth-university] All have wired access to the university's computer network and a support network of residential tutors.
[src:university-of-oxford/aberystwyth-university] Disabled access rooms are available within the existing student village.
[src:university-of-oxford/aberystwyth-university] Aberystwyth University is placed in the UK's top 40 universities in the main national rankings.
[src:university-of-oxford/aberystwyth-university] It is ranked 38th for 132 UK university rankings in *The Times/Sunday Times Good University Guide* for 2023, and the first university to be given the prestigious award "University of the year for teaching quality" for two consecutive years, in 2018 and 2019.
[src:university-of-oxford/aberystwyth-university] The *Times Higher Education World University Rankings* placed it in the 301—350 group for 800 university rankings, compared with 351—400 the previous year, and the *QS World University Rankings* placed it at the 432nd position for 2019, compared with 481—490 of the previous year.
[src:university-of-oxford/aberystwyth-university] In 2015, UK employers from "predominantly business, IT and engineering sectors" listed Aberystwyth equal 49th in their 62-place employability rankings for UK graduates, according to a *Times Higher Education* report.
[src:university-of-oxford/aberystwyth-university] Aberystwyth University was rated in the top ten of UK higher education institutions for overall student satisfaction in the 2016 National Student Survey (NSS).
[src:university-of-oxford/aberystwyth-university] Aberystwyth University was shortlisted in four categories in the *Times Higher Education* Leadership and Management Awards (THELMAs) (2015).
[src:university-of-oxford/aberystwyth-university] Aberystwyth University has been awarded the Silver Award under the Corporate Health Standard (CHS), the quality mark for workplace health promotion run by Welsh Government.
[src:university-of-oxford/aberystwyth-university] The university has been awarded an Athena SWAN Charter Award, recognising commitment to advancing women's careers in science, technology, engineering, maths and medicine (STEMM) in higher education and research.
[src:university-of-oxford/aberystwyth-university] In 2007, the university came under criticism for its record on sustainability, ranking 97th out of 106 UK higher education institutions in that year's Green League table.
[src:university-of-oxford/aberystwyth-university] In 2012 the university was listed in the table's "Failed, no award" section, ranking equal 132nd out of 145.
[src:university-of-oxford/aberystwyth-university] In 2013 it ranked equal 135th out of 143, and was listed again as "Failed, no award".
[src:university-of-oxford/aberystwyth-university] Following the university's initiatives to address sustainability, it received an EcoCampus Silver Phase award in October 2014.
[src:university-of-oxford/aberystwyth-university] In October 2015, the university's Penglais Campus became the first university campus in Wales to achieve the Green Flag Award.
[src:university-of-oxford/aberystwyth-university] The Green Flag Award is a UK-wide partnership, delivered in Wales by Keep Wales Tidy with support from Natural Resources Wales, and is the mark of a high quality park or green space.
[src:university-of-oxford/aberystwyth-university] In 2013, the University and College Union alleged bullying behaviour by Aberystwyth University managers, and said staff were fearful for their jobs.
[src:university-of-oxford/aberystwyth-university] The singer Peter Karrie resigned his honorary fellowship in protest, he said, at the apparent determination to "ruin one of the finest arts centres in the country", and because he was "unable to support any regime that can treat their staff in such a cruel and appalling manner".
[src:university-of-oxford/aberystwyth-university] In Autumn 2024, students protested the reduction of opening hours at Hugh Owen Library, a cost-cutting measure.
[src:university-of-oxford/aberystwyth-university] Students argued that the university had continued to promote their 24/7 Library until recent open days, and that they were going back on promises which had attracted many students to the University.
[src:university-of-oxford/aberystwyth-university] The University initially met with students to discuss options to restore the library's original opening hours, but later rejected further requests for meetings, and refused to negotiate any further.
[src:university-of-oxford/abingdon-and-witney-college] In the early 1960s, the North Berkshire College of Further Education was built.
[src:university-of-oxford/abingdon-and-witney-college] It was renamed to Abingdon College of Further Education sometime after 1974.
[src:university-of-oxford/abingdon-and-witney-college] Abingdon and Whitney College was established in 1 April 2001 after the merger of Abingdon College and West Oxfordshire College.
[src:university-of-oxford/abingdon-and-witney-college] After it underwent a £7.4 million redevelopment, it reopened in July 2012.
[src:university-of-oxford/abingdon-and-witney-college] A new building had been built both on its Abingdon campus, and on its Witney College campus in Witney.
[src:university-of-oxford/abingdon-and-witney-college] The college was graded Good for overall effectiveness, with Outstanding leadership and management, by Ofsted in January 2014, and also graded as 'good' in 2024.
[src:university-of-oxford/abingdon-and-witney-college] In 2015 the college was the No.1 Further Education College in England for 16-18 year old success rates.
[src:university-of-oxford/abingdon-and-witney-college] In June 2015, the Oxfordshire Skills and Learning Service (OSLS) transferred from Oxfordshire County Council to Abingdon & Witney College.
[src:university-of-oxford/abingdon-and-witney-college] In 2024, Jacqui Canton remained CEO of the college as well as Principal.
[src:university-of-oxford/abingdon-and-witney-college] The Abingdon Campus has undergone major refurbishment over the years, with the building work completed in late 2015.
[src:university-of-oxford/abingdon-and-witney-college] Part of the refurbishment was the Advanced Skills Centre, funded by the Local Enterprise Partnership.
[src:university-of-oxford/abingdon-and-witney-college] The redevelopment of the Witney campus was completed in early 2016.
[src:university-of-oxford/abingdon-and-witney-college] Among the new facilities is a television studio.
[src:university-of-oxford/abingdon-and-witney-college] A Construction Skills Centre is also on-site.
[src:university-of-oxford/abingdon-and-witney-college] The Common Leys campus is a 60-acre plot in Hailey, Oxfordshire designed for land-based courses.
[src:university-of-oxford/abingdon-and-witney-college] Witney Stud Farm is based at the Common Leys campus and is home to a thoroughbred stud and equestrian center, which has been awarded a Queen's Anniversary Prize.
[src:university-of-oxford/abingdon-and-witney-college] The facility houses animals such as a family of meerkats, cows, donkeys, sheep, goats, and alpacas.
[src:university-of-oxford/abingdon-and-witney-college] It opened a livestock technology building in May 2019 for agritech classes.
[src:university-of-oxford/abingdon-and-witney-college] It also has a horticulture unit, equine facilities, a dog grooming room, and a canine hydrotherapy center.
[src:university-of-oxford/abingdon-and-witney-college] The Common Leys Campus was graded "outstanding" by Ofsted in January 2014.
[src:university-of-oxford/abingdon-and-witney-college] Abingdon and Witney College is a member of the Land Based Colleges Aspiring to Excellence (Landex).
[src:university-of-oxford/abingdon-and-witney-college] Bicester Construction Skills Centre, opened in 2021, as part of the College's commitment to delivering more apprenticeships across the county, providing over 100 apprentice places each year, including provisions for adults.
[src:university-of-oxford/abingdon-and-witney-college] As well as vocational qualifications, Abingdon & Witney College is an apprenticeship provider.
[src:university-of-oxford/abingdon-and-witney-college] Abingdon & Witney College provides vocational courses for post-16 students, as well as Higher Education, part-time and Professional programmes.
[src:university-of-oxford/abingdon-and-witney-college] Abingdon & Witney College has developed working links with Oxford Brookes University on higher education courses.
[src:university-of-oxford/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] The ***Academic Ranking of World Universities*** (***ARWU***), also known as the **Shanghai Ranking**, is one of the annual publications of world university rankings.
[src:university-of-oxford/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] The league table was originally compiled and issued by Shanghai Jiao Tong University in 2003, making it the first global university ranking with multifarious indicators.
[src:university-of-oxford/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] Since 2009, *ARWU* has been published and copyrighted annually by Shanghai Ranking Consultancy, an organization focusing on higher education that is not legally subordinated to any universities or government agencies.
[src:university-of-oxford/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] In 2011, a board of international advisory consisting of scholars and policy researchers was established to provide suggestions.
[src:university-of-oxford/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] The publication currently includes global league tables for institutions as a whole and for a selection of individual subjects, alongside independent regional *Greater China Ranking* and *Macedonian HEIs Ranking*.
[src:university-of-oxford/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] Altbach named ARWU's 'consistency, clarity of purpose, and transparency' as significant strengths.
[src:university-of-oxford/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] University of Oxford Chancellor Chris Patten has said "the methodology looks fairly solid ... it looks like a pretty good stab at a fair comparison." While ARWU has originated in China, the ranking have been praised for being unbiased towards Asian institutions, especially Chinese institutions.
[src:university-of-oxford/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] The ranking has been criticised for "relying too much on award factors" thus undermining the importance of quality of instruction and humanities.
[src:university-of-oxford/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] A 2007 paper published in the journal *Scientometrics* found that the results from the Shanghai rankings could not be reproduced from raw data using the method described by Liu and Cheng.
[src:university-of-oxford/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] A 2013 paper in the same journal finally showed how the Shanghai ranking results could be reproduced.
[src:university-of-oxford/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] Vincke analyse how the ARWU works, using their insights as specialists of Multiple Criteria Decision Making (MCDM).
[src:university-of-oxford/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] Their main conclusions are that the criteria used are not relevant; that the aggregation methodology has a number of major problems; and that insufficient attention has been paid to fundamental choices of criteria.
[src:university-of-oxford/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] Cheng, think that the quality of universities cannot be precisely measured by mere numbers and any ranking must be controversial.
[src:university-of-oxford/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] They suggest that university and college rankings should be used with caution and their methodologies must be understood clearly before reporting or using the results.
[src:university-of-oxford/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] *ARWU* has been criticised by the European Commission as well as some EU member states for "favour[ing] Anglo-Saxon higher education institutions".
[src:university-of-oxford/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] For instance, *ARWU* is repeatedly criticised in France, where it triggers an annual controversy, focusing on its ill-adapted character to the French academic system and the unreasonable weight given to research often performed decades ago.
[src:university-of-oxford/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] It is also criticised in France for its use as a motivation for merging universities into larger ones.
[src:university-of-oxford/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] Several methods for ranking universities were analyzed.
[src:university-of-oxford/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] Many scholars proposed developing new methodologies for global university rankings, expressing concerns about bias against universities in the Arab region within current ranking systems.
[src:university-of-oxford/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] They emphasized the need to adjust the weighting of indicators to account for overlooked institutional differences.
[src:university-of-oxford/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] There are two categories in *ARWU'*s disciplinary rankings: broad subject fields and specific subjects.
[src:university-of-oxford/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] The methodology is similar to that adopted in the overall table, including award factors, paper citation, and the number of highly cited scholars.
[src:university-of-oxford/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] Considering the development of specific areas, two independent regional league tables with different methodologies were launched – Ranking of Top Universities in Greater China and Best Chinese Universities Ranking.
[src:university-of-oxford/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] Best Chinese Universities Ranking was first released in 2015.
[src:university-of-oxford/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] Ranking of Top Universities in Greater China was first released in 2011.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] The **University of Oxford** is a collegiate research university in Oxford, England.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] There is evidence of teaching as early as 1096, making it the oldest university in the English-speaking world and the world’s second-oldest university in continuous operation.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] It grew rapidly from 1167, when Henry II prohibited English students from attending the University of Paris.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] After escalating conflict between students and the Oxford townspeople, some Oxford academics fled northeast to Cambridge, where they established the University of Cambridge in 1209.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] The two universities share many common features and are jointly referred to as *Oxbridge*.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] Colleges control their own membership and activities.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] Typically social life for students is centred around fellow college members.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] Its buildings and facilities are scattered throughout the city centre and around the town.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] Undergraduate teaching at the university consists of lectures, small-group tutorials at the colleges and halls, seminars, laboratory work and tutorials provided by the central university faculties and departments.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] Postgraduate teaching is provided in a predominantly centralised fashion.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] Oxford operates the Ashmolean Museum, the world's oldest university museum; Oxford University Press, the largest university press in the world; and the largest academic library system nationwide.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] In the fiscal year ending 31 July 2025, the university had a total consolidated income of £3.02 billion, of which £801.3 million was from research grants and contracts.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] Oxford has educated a wide range of notable alumni, including 31 prime ministers of the United Kingdom and many heads of state and government around the world.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] As of October 2025, 76 Nobel Prize laureates, four Fields Medalists, and six Turing Award winners have matriculated, worked, or held visiting fellowships at the University of Oxford.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] Oxford is home to a number of scholarships, including the Rhodes Scholarship, one of the oldest international graduate scholarship programmes in the world.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] The University of Oxford's foundation date is unknown.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] While no official papal bull established Oxford, the university emerged in the 12th century as part of Western Europe's Catholic educational system.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] Nevertheless, a scholarly tradition observable in the 16th century claimed a far earlier 7th-century foundation by Archbishop Theodore of Tarsus (668–690).
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] This claim lacks documentary support, at least in the surviving record.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] Early teaching was conducted by clerics like Theobald of Étampes, and the curriculum focused on theology and canon law, reflecting its ecclesiastical roots.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] Most scholars were members of the clergy until the Reformation.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] In the 1300s, the chronicler Ranulf Higden wrote that the university was founded in the 9th century by Alfred the Great; the story is today considered apocryphal, although it was believed until the 18th century.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] It is known that teaching at Oxford existed in some form as early as 1096, but it is unclear when the university came into being.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] Scholar Theobald of Étampes lectured at Oxford in the early 1100s.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] The university experienced rapid growth beginning in 1167, when King Henry II of England, amid tensions with France and the Church, banned his subjects from studying at the University of Paris.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] King Henry's order prompted many scholars to return and establish a thriving academic community in Oxford.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] The historian Gerald of Wales lectured to such scholars in 1188, and the first known foreign scholar, Emo of Friesland, arrived in 1190.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] The head of the university had the title of chancellor from at least 1214, and the masters were recognised as a *universitas* or corporation in 1231.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] The university was granted a royal charter in 1248 during the reign of King Henry III.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] After disputes between students and Oxford townsfolk in 1209, some academics fled from the violence to Cambridge, later forming the University of Cambridge.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] In later centuries, geographical origins continued to influence many students' affiliations when membership of a college or hall became customary at Oxford.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] Additionally, members of many religious orders, including Dominicans, Franciscans, Carmelites, and Augustinians, settled in Oxford in the mid-13th century, gained influence and maintained houses or halls for students.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] At about the same time, private benefactors established colleges as self-contained scholarly communities.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] Among the earliest such founders were William of Durham, who in 1249 endowed University College, and John Balliol, father of a future King of Scots; Balliol College bears his name.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] Another founder, Walter de Merton, a Lord Chancellor of England and afterwards Bishop of Rochester, composed a series of regulations for college life; Merton College thereby became the model for such establishments at Oxford, as well as at Cambridge.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] Thereafter, an increasing number of students lived in colleges rather than in halls and religious houses.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] In 1333–1334, an attempt by some dissatisfied Oxford scholars to found a new university at Stamford, Lincolnshire, was blocked by the universities of Oxford and Cambridge petitioning King Edward III.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] Thereafter, until the 1820s, no new universities were allowed to be founded in England, even in London; thus, Oxford and Cambridge had a duopoly, which was unusual in large western European countries.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] The new learning of the Renaissance greatly influenced Oxford from the late 15th century onwards.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] Among university scholars of the period were William Grocyn, who contributed to the revival of Greek language studies, and John Colet, the noted biblical scholar.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] With the English Reformation and the break of communion with the Roman Catholic Church, recusant scholars from Oxford fled to continental Europe, settling especially at the University of Douai.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] The method of teaching at Oxford was transformed from the medieval scholastic method to Renaissance education, although institutions associated with the university experienced losses of land and revenues.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] As a centre of learning and scholarship, Oxford's reputation declined in the Age of Enlightenment; enrolments fell and teaching was neglected.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] In 1636, William Laud, the chancellor and Archbishop of Canterbury, codified the university's statutes.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] These, for the most part, remained its governing regulations until the mid-19th century.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] Laud was also responsible for the granting of a charter securing privileges for the University Press, and he made notable contributions to the Bodleian Library, the main library of the university.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] From the beginnings of the Church of England as the established church until 1866, membership of the church was a requirement to graduate as a Bachelor of Arts, and Dissenters were only permitted to be promoted to Master of Arts starting in 1871.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] The university was a centre of the Royalist party during the English Civil War (1642–1651), while the town favoured the opposing Parliamentarian cause.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] Wadham College, founded in 1610, was the undergraduate college of Sir Christopher Wren.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] He was part of a group of experimental scientists at Oxford in the 1650s, the Oxford Philosophical Club, which included Robert Boyle and Robert Hooke.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] This group, which has at times been linked with Boyle's "Invisible College", held regular meetings at Wadham under the guidance of the college's warden, John Wilkins, and the group formed the nucleus that went on to found the Royal Society.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] In 1827, a major review of the university's statutes, some over 500 years old, was conducted.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] Among the changes made at this time was the removal of the requirement that students swear an oath of enmity towards an Oxford townsman Henry Symeonis, who was found guilty of murdering an Oxford student in the mid-13th century.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] Before reforms in the early 19th century, the curriculum at Oxford was notoriously narrow and impractical.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] Sir Spencer Walpole, a historian of contemporary Great Britain and a senior government official, had not attended any university.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] Of the students who matriculated in 1840, 65% were sons of professionals (34% were Anglican ministers).
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] After graduation, 87% became professionals (59% as Anglican clergy).
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] Out of the students who matriculated in 1870, 59% were sons of professionals (25% were Anglican ministers).
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] After graduation, 87% became professionals (42% as Anglican clergy).
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] Jones argue that the rise of organised sport was one of the most remarkable and distinctive features of the history of the universities of Oxford and Cambridge during the late 19th and early 20th centuries.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] It was carried over from the athleticism prevalent at the public schools such as Eton, Winchester, Shrewsbury, and Harrow.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] All students, regardless of their chosen area of study, were required to spend (at least) their first year preparing for a first-year examination that was heavily focused on classical languages.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] Science students found this particularly burdensome and supported a separate science degree with Greek language study removed from their required courses.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] This concept of a Bachelor of Science had been adopted at other European universities (London University had implemented it in 1860) but an 1880 proposal at Oxford to replace the classical requirement with a modern language (like German or French) was unsuccessful.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] After considerable internal haggling over the structure of the arts curriculum, in 1886 the "natural science preliminary" was recognised as a qualifying part of the first year examination.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] At the start of 1914, the university housed about 3,000 undergraduates and around 100 postgraduate students.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] During the First World War, many undergraduates and fellows joined the armed forces.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] By 1918 nearly all fellows were serving in uniform, and the student population in residence was reduced to 12% of the pre-war total.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] The University Roll of Service records that, in total, 14,792 members of the university served in the war, with 2,716 (18.36%) killed.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] During the war years the university buildings became hospitals, cadet schools and military training camps.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] Two parliamentary commissions in 1852 issued recommendations for Oxford and Cambridge.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] Archibald Campbell Tait, a former headmaster of Rugby School, was a key member of the Oxford Commission; he wanted Oxford to follow the German and Scottish model in which the professorship was paramount.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] The commission's report envisioned a centralised university run predominantly by professors and faculties, with a much stronger emphasis on research.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] The professional staff should be strengthened and better paid.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] For students, restrictions on entry should be dropped, and more opportunities given to poorer families.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] It called for an expansion of the curriculum, with honours to be awarded in many new fields.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] Undergraduate scholarships should be open to all Britons.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] Graduate fellowships should be opened up to all members of the university.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] It recommended that fellows be released from an obligation for ordination.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] Students were to be allowed to save money by boarding in the city, instead of in one of the colleges.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] The system of separate honour schools for different subjects began in 1802, with Mathematics and Literae Humaniores.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] Schools of "Natural Sciences" and "Law, and Modern History" were added in 1853.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] By 1872, the last of these had split into "Jurisprudence" and "Modern History".
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] Theology became the sixth honour school.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] Honours degrees, the postgraduate Bachelor of Civil Law (B.C.L.) was, and still is, offered.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] The mid-19th century saw the impact of the Oxford Movement (1833–1845), led, among others, by the future Cardinal John Henry Newman.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] Administrative reforms during the 19th century included the replacement of oral examinations with written entrance tests, greater tolerance for religious dissent, and the establishment of four women's colleges.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] Privy Council decisions in the 20th century - the abolition of compulsory daily worship, dissociation of the Regius Professorship of Hebrew from clerical status, diversion of colleges' theological bequests to other purposes - loosened the link with traditional belief and practice.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] Furthermore, although the university's emphasis had historically been on classical knowledge, its curriculum expanded during the 19th century to include scientific and medical studies.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] The postgraduate degrees of Bachelor of Science and Bachelor of Letters (renamed Master of Science and Master of Letters in the 1970s) were introduced in 1895, and the university began to award doctorates for research in 1900 with the Doctor of Letters and Doctor of Science degrees.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] Oxford was the first British university to institute a Doctor of Philosophy degree (abbreviated DPhil) in 1917; it was first awarded in 1919 to Lakshman Sarup of Balliol College.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] The university passed a statute in 1875 allowing examinations for women at a level approximately equivalent to undergraduate studies; for a brief period in the early 1900s, this allowed the "steamboat ladies" to receive *ad eundem* degrees from the University of Dublin.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] In June 1878, the Association for the Education of Women (AEW) was formed, aiming for the eventual creation of a college for women in Oxford.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] Some of the more prominent members of the association were George Granville Bradley, T.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] Talbot insisted on a specifically Anglican institution, which was unacceptable to most of the other members.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] The two parties eventually split, and Talbot's group founded Lady Margaret Hall in 1878, while T.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] Green founded the non-denominational Somerville College in 1879.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] Lady Margaret Hall and Somerville opened their doors to their first 21 students (12 at Somerville, 9 at Lady Margaret Hall) in 1879, who attended lectures in rooms above an Oxford baker's shop.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] There were also 25 women students living at home or with friends in 1879, a group which evolved into the Society of Oxford Home-Students and in 1952 into St Anne's College.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] These first three societies for women were followed by St Hugh's (1886) and St Hilda's (1893).
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] All of these colleges later became coeducational, starting with Lady Margaret Hall and St Anne's in 1979, and finishing with St Hilda's, which began to accept male students in 2008.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] In the early 20th century, Oxford and Cambridge were widely perceived to be bastions of male privilege; however, the integration of women into Oxford moved forward during the First World War.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] In 1916 women were admitted as medical students on a par with men, and in 1917 the university accepted financial responsibility for women's examinations.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] On 7 October 1920 women became eligible for admission as full members of the university and were given the right to take degrees.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] In 1927 the university's dons created a quota that limited the number of female students to a quarter that of men, a ruling which was not abolished until 1957.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] Additionally, during this period Oxford colleges were single sex, so the number of women was also limited by the capacity of the women's colleges to admit students.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] It was not until 1959 that the women's colleges were given full collegiate status.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] In 1974, Brasenose, Jesus, Wadham, Hertford and St Catherine's became the first formerly all-male colleges to admit women.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] The majority of men's colleges accepted their first female students in 1979, with Christ Church following in 1980, and Oriel becoming the last men's college to admit women in 1985.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] Most of Oxford's graduate colleges were founded as coeducational establishments in the 20th century, with the exception of St Antony's, which was founded as a men's college in 1950 and began to accept women only in 1962.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] By 1988, 40% of undergraduates at Oxford were female; in 2016, 45% of the student population, and 47% of undergraduate students, were female.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] In June 2017, Oxford announced that starting in the 2018 academic year, history students may choose to sit a take-home exam in some courses, with the intention that this will equalise rates of firsts awarded to women and men at Oxford.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] That same summer, maths and computer science tests were extended by 15 minutes, in a bid to see if female student scores would improve.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] The detective novel *Gaudy Night* by Dorothy L.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] Sayers, one of the first women to gain an academic degree from Oxford, is largely set in the all-female Shrewsbury College, Oxford (based on Sayers' own Somerville College), and the issue of women's education is central to its plot.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] Social historian and Somerville College alumna Jane Robinson's book *Bluestockings: A Remarkable History of the First Women to Fight for an Education* gives a very detailed and immersive account of this history.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] The university is a "city university" in that it does not have a main campus; instead, colleges, departments, accommodation, and other facilities are scattered throughout central Oxford and in some other areas of the city.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] The Science Area, in which most science departments are located, is the area that bears closest resemblance to a campus.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] There is a ten-acre (4-hectare) Radcliffe Observatory Quarter in the northwest of the city.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] Iconic university buildings include the Radcliffe Camera, the Sheldonian Theatre used for music concerts, lectures, and university ceremonies, and the Examination Schools, where examinations and some lectures take place.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] The University Church of St Mary the Virgin was used for university ceremonies before the construction of the Sheldonian.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] In 2012–2013, the university built the controversial one-hectare (400 m × 25 m) Castle Mill development of 4–5-storey blocks of student flats overlooking Cripley Meadow and the historic Port Meadow, blocking views of the spires in the city centre.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] The development has been likened to building a "skyscraper beside Stonehenge".
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] The University Parks are a 70-acre (28 ha) parkland area in the northeast of the city, near Keble College, Somerville College and Lady Margaret Hall.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] It is open to the public during daylight hours.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] There are also various college-owned open spaces open to the public, including Bagley Wood and most notably Christ Church Meadow.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] The Botanic Garden on the High Street is the oldest botanic garden in the UK.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] It contains over 8,000 different plant species on 1.8 ha (4+1⁄2 acres).
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] It is one of the most diverse yet compact major collections of plants in the world and includes representatives of over 90% of the higher plant families.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] The Harcourt Arboretum is a 130-acre (53 ha) site six miles (9.7 km) south of the city that includes native woodland and 67 acres (27 hectares) of meadow.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] The 1,000-acre (4.0 km2) Wytham Woods are owned by the university and used for research in zoology and climate change.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] Colleges arrange the tutorial teaching for their undergraduates, and the members of an academic department are spread around many colleges.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] Though certain colleges do have subject alignments (e.g., Nuffield College as a centre for the social sciences), these are exceptions, and most colleges will have a diverse community of students and academics representing a wide range of disciplines.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] Facilities such as libraries are provided on all these levels: by the central university (the Bodleian), by the departments (individual departmental libraries, such as the English Faculty Library), and by colleges (each of which maintains a multi-discipline library for the use of its members).
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] The university's formal head is the chancellor, with Lord Hague of Richmond inaugurated in 2025 although, as at most British universities, the chancellor is a titular figurehead and is not involved with the day-to-day running of the university.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] The chancellor is elected by the members of convocation, a body comprising all graduates of the university, and may hold office until death.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] The vice-chancellor, currently Irene Tracey, is the *de facto* head of the university.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] There are five pro-vice-chancellors with specific responsibilities.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] Two university proctors, elected annually on a rotating basis from any two of the colleges, are the internal ombudsmen who make sure that the university and its members adhere to its statutes.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] This role incorporates student discipline and complaints, as well as oversight of the university's proceedings.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] The university's professors are collectively referred to as the Statutory Professors of the University of Oxford.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] They are particularly influential in the running of the university's graduate programmes.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] Examples of statutory professors are the Chichele Professorships and the Drummond Professor of Political Economy.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] Oxford is a "public university" in that it receives some public money from the government, but it is a "private university" in that it is entirely self-governing and, in theory, could choose to become entirely private by rejecting public funds.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] To be a member of the university, all students, and most academic staff, must also be a member of a college or hall.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] There are thirty-nine colleges of the University of Oxford and four permanent private halls (PPHs), each controlling its membership and with its own internal structure and activities.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] Not all colleges offer all courses, but they generally cover a broad range of subjects.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] ‡ These three have no royal charter, and are officially departments of the university rather than independent colleges.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] The permanent private halls were founded by different Christian denominations.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] One difference between a college and a PPH is that whereas colleges are governed by the fellows of the college, the governance of a PPH resides, at least in part, with the corresponding Christian denomination.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] The PPHs and colleges join as the Conference of Colleges, which represents their common concerns, to discuss matters of shared interest and to act collectively when necessary, such as in dealings with the central university.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] The Conference of Colleges was established as a recommendation of the Franks Commission in 1965.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] Teaching members of the colleges (i.e. fellows and tutors) are collectively and familiarly known as dons, although the term is rarely used by the university itself.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] In addition to residential and dining facilities, the colleges provide social, cultural, and recreational activities for their members.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] Colleges have responsibility for admitting undergraduates and organising their tuition; for graduates, this responsibility falls upon the departments.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] The combined endowment figure of £8.708 billion makes Oxford hold the largest endowment of any university in the UK.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] The college figure does not reflect all the assets held by the colleges as their accounts do not include the cost or value of many of their main sites or heritage assets such as works of art or libraries.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] The central University's endowment, along with some of the colleges', is managed by the university's wholly owned endowment management office, Oxford University Endowment Management, formed in 2007.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] The university used to maintain substantial investments in fossil fuel companies.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] However, in April 2020, the university committed to divest from direct investments in fossil fuel companies and to require indirect investments in fossil fuel companies be subjected to the Oxford Martin Principles.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] The university was one of the first in the UK to raise money through a major public fundraising campaign, the Campaign for Oxford.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] The current campaign, its second, was launched in May 2008 and is entitled "Oxford Thinking – The Campaign for the University of Oxford".
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] This is looking to support three areas: academic posts and programmes, student support, and buildings and infrastructure; having passed its original target of £1.25 billion in March 2012, the target was raised to £3 billion.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] The university has faced criticism for some of its sources of donations and funding.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] In 2017, attention was drawn to historical donations including All Souls College receiving £10,000 from slave trader Christopher Codrington in 1710, and Oriel College receiving £100,000 from the will of the imperialist Cecil Rhodes in 1902.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] In 1996 a donation of £20 million was received from Wafic Saïd who was involved in the Al-Yammah arms deal, and taking £150 million from the US billionaire businessman Stephen A.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] The university has defended its decisions saying it "takes legal, ethical and reputational issues into consideration".
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] The university also faced criticism, as noted above, over its decision to accept donations from fossil fuel companies having received £21.8 million from the fossil fuel industry between 2010 and 2015, £18.8 million between 2015 and 2020 and £1.6 million between 2020 and 2021.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] The university accepted £6 million from The Alexander Mosley Charitable Trust in 2021.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] Former racing driver Max Mosley stated that he set up the trust "to house the fortune he inherited" from his father, Oswald Mosley, who was founder of two far-right groups: Union Movement and the British Union of Fascists.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] Oxford is a member of the Russell Group of research-led British universities and is regarded to be part of the non-formal grouping of universities which make up the "golden triangle" in South East England.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p01] Internationally, it is a member of the Europaeum, the League of European Research Universities, and the International Alliance of Research Universities.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] The Sutton Trust maintains that Oxford University and Cambridge University recruit undergraduates disproportionately from 8 schools which accounted for 1,310 Oxbridge places during three years, contrasted with 1,220 from 2,900 other schools.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] To allow a more individualised judgement of students, who might otherwise apply for both, undergraduate applicants are not permitted to apply to both Oxford and Cambridge in the same year.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] The only exceptions are applicants for organ scholarships and those applying to read for a second undergraduate degree.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] Oxford has the lowest offer rate of all Russell Group universities.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] Most applicants choose to apply to one of the individual colleges.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] Undergraduate applicants benefit from the collaborative efforts of the colleges, which aim to ensure that top students secure a place at the university, regardless of their initial college choices.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] Postgraduate applicants who are offered admission by the university are assured a place in one of the colleges, even if their preferred college cannot accommodate them.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] Undergraduate shortlisting is based on achieved and predicted exam results, school references, and, in some subjects, written admission tests or candidate-submitted written work.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] Approximately 60% of applicants are shortlisted, although this varies by subject.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] If a large number of shortlisted applicants for a subject choose one college, then students who named that college may be reallocated randomly to under-subscribed colleges for the subject.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] The colleges then invite shortlisted candidates for interview, where they are provided with food and accommodation for around three days in December.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] Most undergraduate applicants will be individually interviewed by academics at more than one college.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] In 2020 interviews were moved online, and they will remain online until at least 2027.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] Undergraduate offers are sent out in early January, with each offer usually being from a specific college.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] One in four successful candidates receives an offer from a college that they did not apply to.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] Some courses may make "open offers" to some candidates, who are not assigned to a particular college until A Level results day in August.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] The university has come under criticism for the number of students it accepts from private schools; for instance, Laura Spence's rejection from the university in 2000 led to widespread debate.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] In 2016, the University of Oxford gave 59% of offers to UK students to students from state schools, while about 93% of all UK pupils and 86% of post-16 UK pupils are educated in state schools.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] However, 64% of UK applicants were from state schools and the university notes that state school students apply disproportionately to oversubscribed subjects.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] The proportion of students coming from state schools has been increasing.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] Oxford University spends over £6 million per year on outreach programs to encourage applicants from underrepresented demographics.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] In 2018 the university's annual admissions report revealed that eight of Oxford's colleges had accepted fewer than three black applicants in the past three years.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] Labour MP David Lammy said, "This is social apartheid and it is utterly unrepresentative of life in modern Britain." In 2020, Oxford had increased its proportion of Black, Asian and Minority Ethnic (BAME) students to record levels.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] The number of BAME undergraduates accepted to the university in 2020 rose to 684 students, or 23.6% of the UK intake, up from 558 or 22% in 2019; the number of Black students was 106 (3.7% of the intake), up from 80 students (3.2%).
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] UCAS data also showed that Oxford is more likely than comparable institutions to make offers to ethnic minority and socially disadvantaged pupils.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] Based on 2022/23 HESA entry standards data published in domestic league tables, which include a broad range of qualifications beyond the top three exam grades, the average student at the University of Oxford achieved 203 points – the fourth highest score in the United Kingdom.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] The university itself is responsible for conducting examinations and conferring degrees.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] Undergraduate teaching takes place during three eight-week academic terms: Michaelmas, Hilary and Trinity.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] Undergraduates must be in residence from Thursday of 0th week.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] These teaching terms are shorter than those of most other British universities, and their total duration amounts to less than half the year.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] However, undergraduates are also expected to do some academic work during the three holidays (known as the Christmas, Easter, and Long Vacations).
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] There are many opportunities for students at Oxford to receive financial help during their studies.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] The Oxford Opportunity Bursaries, introduced in 2006, are university-wide means-based bursaries available to any British undergraduate, with a total possible grant of £10,235 over a 3-year degree.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] In addition, individual colleges also offer bursaries and funds to help their students.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] For graduate study, there are many scholarships attached to the university, available to students from all sorts of backgrounds, from Rhodes Scholarships to the relatively new Weidenfeld Scholarships.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] Oxford also offers the Clarendon Scholarship which is open to graduate applicants of all nationalities.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] The Clarendon Scholarship is principally funded by Oxford University Press in association with colleges and other partnership awards.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] In 2016, Oxford University announced that it is to run its first free online economics course as part of a "massive open online course" (MOOC) scheme, in partnership with a US online university network.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] The course available is called 'From Poverty to Prosperity: Understanding Economic Development'.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] Students successful in early examinations are rewarded by their colleges with scholarships and exhibitions, normally the result of a long-standing endowment, although since the introduction of tuition fees the amounts of money available are purely nominal.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] Scholars, and exhibitioners in some colleges, are entitled to wear a more voluminous undergraduate gown; "commoners" (originally those who had to pay for their "commons", or food and lodging) are restricted to a short, sleeveless garment.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] The term "scholar" in relation to Oxford therefore has a specific meaning as well as the more general meaning of someone of outstanding academic ability.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] In previous times, there were "noblemen commoners" and "gentlemen commoners", but these ranks were abolished in the 19th century.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] "Closed" scholarships, available only to candidates who fitted specific conditions such as coming from specific schools, were abolished in the 1970s and 1980s.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] The university maintains the largest university library system in the UK, and, with over 11 million volumes housed on 120 miles (190 km) of shelving, the Bodleian group is the second-largest library in the UK, after the British Library.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] The Bodleian is a legal deposit library, which means that it is entitled to request a free copy of every book published in the UK.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] As such, its collection is growing at a rate of over three miles (five kilometres) of shelving every year.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] The buildings referred to as the university's main research library, The Bodleian, consist of the original Bodleian Library in the Old Schools Quadrangle, founded by Sir Thomas Bodley in 1598 and opened in 1602, the Radcliffe Camera, the Clarendon Building, and the Weston Library.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] A tunnel underneath Broad Street connects these buildings, with the Gladstone Link, which opened to readers in 2011, connecting the Old Bodleian and Radcliffe Camera.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] The Bodleian Libraries group was formed in 2000, bringing the Bodleian Library and some of the subject libraries together.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] It now comprises 28 libraries, a number of which have been created by bringing previously separate collections together, including the Sackler Library, Law Library, Social Science Library and Radcliffe Science Library.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] A new book depository opened in South Marston, Swindon, in October 2010, and recent building projects include the remodelling of the New Bodleian building, which was renamed the Weston Library when it reopened in 2015.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] The renovation is designed to better showcase the library's various treasures (which include a Shakespeare First Folio and a Gutenberg Bible) as well as temporary exhibitions.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] The Bodleian engaged in a mass-digitisation project with Google in 2004.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] Notable electronic resources hosted by the Bodleian Group include the *Electronic Enlightenment Project*, which was awarded the 2010 Digital Prize by the British Society for Eighteenth-Century Studies.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] Oxford maintains a number of museums and galleries, open for free to the public.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] The Ashmolean Museum, founded in 1683, is the oldest museum in the UK, and the oldest university museum in the world.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] It holds significant collections of art and archaeology, including works by Michelangelo, Leonardo da Vinci, Turner, and Picasso, as well as treasures such as the Scorpion Macehead, the Parian Marble and the Alfred Jewel.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] It also contains "The Messiah", a pristine Stradivarius violin, regarded by some as one of the finest examples in existence.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] The University Museum of Natural History holds the university's zoological, entomological and geological specimens.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] It is housed in a large neo-Gothic building on Parks Road, in the university's Science Area.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] Among its collection are the skeletons of a *Tyrannosaurus rex* and *Triceratops*, and the most complete remains of a dodo found anywhere in the world.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] It also hosts the Simonyi Professorship of the Public Understanding of Science, currently held by Marcus du Sautoy.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] Adjoining the Museum of Natural History is the Pitt Rivers Museum, founded in 1884, which displays the university's archaeological and anthropological collections, currently holding over 500,000 items.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] It recently built a new research annexe; its staff have been involved with the teaching of anthropology at Oxford since its foundation, when as part of his donation General Augustus Pitt Rivers stipulated that the university establish a lectureship in anthropology.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] The Museum of the History of Science is housed on Broad Street in the world's oldest-surviving purpose-built museum building.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] It contains 15,000 artefacts, from antiquity to the 20th century, representing almost all aspects of the history of science.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] In the Faculty of Music on St Aldate's is the Bate Collection of Musical Instruments, a collection mostly of instruments from Western classical music, from the medieval period onwards.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] Christ Church Picture Gallery holds a large collection of old master paintings and drawings.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] The Oxford University Press is the world's second oldest and currently the largest university press by the number of publications.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] Due to its age and its social and academic status, the University of Oxford is considered to be one of Britain's most prestigious or elite universities and to form, along with the University of Cambridge, a top two that stand above other UK universities in this regard.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] Oxford is regularly ranked within the top five universities in the world in the *Times Higher Education World University Rankings*, as well as the Forbes's World University Rankings.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] In 2021, it ranked sixth among the universities around the world by SCImago Institutions Rankings.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] The *THE* has also recognised Oxford as one of the world's "six super brands" on its *World Reputation Rankings*, along with Berkeley, Cambridge, Harvard, MIT, and Stanford.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] The university is fourth worldwide on the *US News* ranking.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] Its Saïd Business School came 13th in the world in *Financial Times* *Global MBA Ranking*.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] The university was ranked first in the world in *Time* magazine's 2026 ranking.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] Oxford was ranked 13th in the world in 2022 by the Nature Index, which measures the largest contributors to papers published in 82 leading journals.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] It is ranked fifth best university worldwide and first in Britain for forming CEOs according to the *Professional Ranking World Universities*, and first in the UK for the quality of its graduates as chosen by the recruiters of the UK's major companies.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] In the 2018 *Complete University Guide*, all 38 subjects offered by Oxford rank within the top 10 nationally meaning Oxford was one of only two multi-faculty universities (along with Cambridge) in the UK to have 100% of their subjects in the top 10.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] Computer Science, Medicine, Philosophy, Politics and Psychology were ranked first in the UK by the guide.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] According to the QS World University Rankings by Subject, the University of Oxford also ranks as number one in the world for four Humanities disciplines: English Language and Literature, Modern Languages, Geography, and History.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] It also ranks second globally for Anthropology, Archaeology, Law, Medicine, Politics & International Studies, and Psychology.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] Academic dress is required for examinations, matriculation, disciplinary hearings, and when visiting university officers.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] A referendum held among the Oxford student body in 2015 showed 76% against making it voluntary in examinations – 8,671 students voted, with the 40.2% turnout the highest ever for a UK student union referendum.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] This was widely interpreted by students as being a vote not so much on making subfusc voluntary, but, in effect, on abolishing it by default, in that if a minority of people came to exams without subfusc, the rest would soon follow.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] In July 2012 the regulations regarding academic dress were modified to be more inclusive to transgender people.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] 'Trashing' is a tradition of spraying those who just finished their last examination of the year with alcohol, flour and confetti.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] The sprayed student stays in the academic dress worn to the exam.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] The custom began in the 1970s when friends of students taking their finals waited outside Oxford's Examination Schools where exams for most degrees are taken.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] Other traditions and customs vary by college.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] For example, some colleges have formal hall six times a week, but in others this only happens occasionally, or even not at all.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] *Balls* are major events held by colleges; the largest, held triennially in ninth week of Trinity Term, are known as commemoration balls; the dress code is usually white tie.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] Many other colleges hold smaller events during the year that they call summer balls or parties.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] The Oxford Union (distinct from Oxford University Student Union) is an independent debating society which hosts weekly debates and high-profile speakers.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] Party political groups include Oxford University Conservative Association and Oxford University Labour Club.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] Most academic areas have student societies of some form, for example the Scientific Society.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] There are two weekly student newspapers: the independent *Cherwell* and OUSU's *The Oxford Student*.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] Other publications include the *Isis* magazine, the satirical *Oxymoron*, the graduate *Oxonian Review*, the *Oxford Political Review*, and the online only newspaper *The Oxford Blue*.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] The student radio station is Oxide Radio.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] Sport is played between college teams, in tournaments known as cuppers (the term is also used for some non-sporting competitions).
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] In particular, much attention is given to the termly intercollegiate rowing regattas: Christ Church Regatta, Torpids, and Summer Eights.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] In addition, there are higher standard university wide teams.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] Significant focus is given to annual varsity matches played against Cambridge, the most famous of which is The Boat Race, watched by a TV audience of between five and ten million viewers.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] A blue is an award given to those who compete at the university team level in certain sports.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] Music, drama, and other arts societies exist both at the collegiate level and as university-wide groups, such as the Oxford University Dramatic Society and the Oxford Revue.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] The Oxford Imps, a comedy improvisation troupe, perform weekly at The Jericho Tavern during term time.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] Private members' clubs for students include Vincent's Club (primarily for sportspeople) and The Gridiron Club.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] A number of invitation-only student dining clubs also exist, including the Bullingdon Club.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] The importance of collegiate life is such that for many students their college JCR (Junior Common Room, for undergraduates) or MCR (Middle Common Room, for graduates) is seen as more important than OUSU.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] JCRs and MCRs each have a committee, with a president and other elected students representing their peers to college authorities.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] Additionally, they organise events and often have significant budgets to spend as they wish (money coming from their colleges and sometimes other sources such as student-run bars).
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] Throughout its history, a sizeable number of Oxford alumni, known as Oxonians, have become notable in many varied fields, both academic and otherwise.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] More than 70 Nobel prize-winners have studied or taught at Oxford, with prizes won in all six categories.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] More information on notable members of the university can be found in the individual college articles.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] An individual may be associated with two or more colleges, as an undergraduate, postgraduate or member of staff.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] Notable alumni include three Fields Medallists, two British kings and at least fifteen monarchs of eleven other sovereign states (including five reigning monarchs), thirty-one British prime ministers, and thirty-five presidents and prime ministers of nineteen other countries.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] As of July 2019 there are seven Oxonians in the Cabinet of the United Kingdom and two in the Shadow Cabinet.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] The University of Oxford is the setting for numerous works of fiction.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] The school was mentioned in fiction as early as 1400 when Chaucer, in *Canterbury Tales*, referred to a "Clerk [student] of Oxenford".
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] Mortimer Proctor argues the first campus novel was *The Adventures of Oxymel Classic, Esq; Once an Oxford Scholar* (1768).
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] It is filled with violence and debauchery, with obnoxious, foolish dons becoming easy prey for cunning students.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] Proctor argues that by 1900, "novels about Oxford and Cambridge were so numerous that they clearly represent a striking literary phenomenon." By 1989, 533 novels based in Oxford had been identified and the number continues to rise.
[src:university-of-oxford/university-of-oxford-p02] Notable non-fiction works on Oxford include *Oxford* by Jan Morris.
